<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Calls Emergency Council Meeting on UNSCOM's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Tuesday called an
emergency meeting of the United Nations Security Council to
discuss what U.N weapons inspectors had left in their offices in
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after the Council meeting, Russian
Ambassador to the United Nations, Sergery Lavrov, said the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction had left some chemical
substances in their laboratory which was located in the Canal
Hotel in Baghdad before they withdrew last December.
</P>
<P>
Lavrov said this information came to Russia's knowledge only
days ago and Russia requested the further information about it.
</P>
<P>
Lavrov said Richard Butler, Executive Chairman of UNSCOM, was
asked to gave explanations about it at the meeting, and Butler
said nothing was dangerous there.
</P>
<P>
Council President for the current month Ismaila Jagne of Gambia
said Butler was requested to submit a report to give further
information.
</P>
<P>
Ismaila Jagne said the Council might get the report tonight and
the Council was scheduled to meet on the report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has not gone back to Iraq to resume its work since the
U.S.-led military strikes against the country last December.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has accused UNSCOM of spying for the United States and
vowed not to cooperate with it any longer.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has been sharply divided on its policy
towards Iraq, especially on the future of UNSCOM. There are
initials which suggest UNSCOM be replaced by a new institution and
the Council has not reached agreement on it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
