<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Convenes Special Session on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu convened his inner cabinet meeting for a
special session Tuesday night on the situation in South Lebanon,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio report said Netanyahu summoned the cabinet of
selected key ministers, including Defense Minister Moshe Arens and
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, on a two-hour notice.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's office issued a terse statement after the session
that the ministers were updated by top security officials with
informations on the withdrawal of Israel-backed Lebanese militia
from the South Lebanon enclave of Jezzine and the activities of
the Israeli army in the security zone.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Arens and Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz
briefed Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak on the situation in
Lebanon, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA) Tuesday continued its
withdrawal from Jezzine north of the security zone, a
15-kilometer-deep buffer zone carved out by Israel in 1985 to
prevent cross-border attacks by Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Two SLA soldiers were killed and one was wounded by roadside
bombs planted by Hezbollah guerrillas while the militiamen
abandoned outlying positions and withdrew into the town of
Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Israeli warplanes struck repeatedly suspected
Hezbollah bases around Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
The SLA withdrawal from Jezzine, which began Monday night, is
seen by some as a possible prelude to a full Israeli withdrawal
from South Lebanon, but Israel has denied any connection between
them, emphasizing that an SLA withdrawal from Jezzine was purely
the decision of SLA leaders because casualties had become too
high.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who defeated Netanyahu in the elections last month, has
promised that he will pull Israeli troops out of South Lebanon
within a year since he comes to power through agreement with
Syria, the main power-broker in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
