<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, June 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak is
considering whether to, through consultations with the United
States and the Palestinians, drop the latest interim peace
agreement and jump to final status talks, the Haaretz daily
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Labor sources as saying that Barak's
consideration is based on the premise that the broad coalition he
is trying to put together will have the necessary political clout
to make a final status deal, making the interim steps stipulated
in the Wye agreement unnecessary any more. (BC-Israel-Wye)
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Three Syiran workers were wounded Tuesday in Israeli
air raids on Lebanese guerrillas' targets in south Lebanon, the
Voice of the People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted security sources as saying that Israeli
warplanes fired several missiles on Hezbollah guerrilla's
strongholds in Iqlim Toufah, north of the Israeli occupied border
zone in south Lebanon. (BC-Lebanon-Israel-Wounded)
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Amid heavy attacks by Lebanese guerrillas, the
pro-Israeli militia South Lebanon Army (SLA) Tuesday started a
pullout from Jezzine in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The SLA militiamen knocked down earth mounds and dynamited
fortified positions in and around Jezzine, just north of the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Truck convoys were also seen streaming out of the beleaguered
town, carrying artillery and motor guns, equipment, ammunition and
household furniture to the Israeli self-declared security zone
which it set up in 1985 to shield its northern flank from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
(BC-Lebanon-SLA-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Abdullah Ocalan, leader of Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), Tuesday confessed at his trial that many
Middle East and European countries and clandestine groups had
collaborated with his group.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Ankara Security Court No. 2 on Monday started the
trial of Ocalan on charges of treason on the Imrali Island near
Turkey's western province of Bursa.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions by the presiding judge of the trial,
Ocalan listed Syria, Greece, Cyprus, Iran, Iraq, Yugoslavia,
Armenia, Britain, Greek Orthodox Church and clandestine
extreme-left Turkish groups as some of the collaborators of the
PKK, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported Tuesday.
(BC-Turkey-PKK) 
</P>
</TEXT>
