<HEADLINE> Iraqi Civilian Targets Bombed by U.S. Warplanes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Some Iraqi civilian targets in the
south of the country were bombed on Tuesday by U.S. and British
planes, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman said that at 10:50 (0650 GMT) and
17: 00 (1300 GMT) 32 formations of enemy warplanes coming from
Kuwaiti and Saudi airspace violated southern Iraqi airspace over
the provinces of Basra, Thi-Qar, Qadissiya, Misan and Muthana.
</P>
<P>
He said that the enemy formations attacked civilian targets
in the region, adding that Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back
and forced the enemy planes to flee at 19:20 (1520 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The spokesman did not mention whether casualties were caused.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched four-night airstrikes
against Iraq last December, their warplanes have been regularly
attacking Iraqi military and civilian targets in the no-fly zones,
causing severe civilian casualties and property damages.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared that it does not recognize these restricted
zones and vowed to continue confronting any allied plane violating
its airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Criticizes Turkey for Claims on Greek Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday criticized
neighboring Turkey's tactics of improving bilateral ties while at
the same time making claims on Greek territory.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the letter by Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
to his Greek counterpart George Papandreou, Reppas said at a press
briefing that good relations between the two neighbors required
the corresponding stance from both sides, something that Turkey
was not doing.
</P>
<P>
He urged Turkey to go beyond words to deeds.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Cem called for cooperation and bettering
relations between Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit Monday also urged Greece
to start a dialogue on disputes between the two countries over the
ownership of islets in the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have been at odds over decades for their
disputes in the territorial waters, air space limits and the
delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean Sea, and the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Greece has repeatedly said that Turkey should take its
unilateral claims to questioning Greek sovereignty over a number
of uninhabited islets in the eastern Aegean Sea to the
International Court of Justice in the Hague, but Turkey has
refused to do so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
