<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Economy Expands in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. industrial economy
expanded for a fourth straight month in May and prices paid by
manufacturers rose in the same period, said the National
Association of Purchasing Management Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The association said in a report that its monthly index of
business activity rose to 55.2 in May from 52.8 in April and its
index of prices paid by manufacturers rose in the same month to
52.2 percent for the first time in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
The results have sent the stock market lower in morning session
in fears of high inflation and interest rates. The Federal Reserve
warned two weeks ago that it would raise interest rates to cool
off the economy if inflation is building up.
</P>
<P>
But The Conference Board sent different economic signals. The
private research group reported the index of leading economic
indicators declined 0.1 percent in April to 107.1 for the first
time since June, 1998, suggesting some softening in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Commerce Department said in its report that
construction spending fell by a sharp 2.4 percent in April, the
biggest monthly decline in more than five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
