<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges Greece to Cooperate Against Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
urged Greece to offer cooperation in fighting against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to his Greek counterpart George Papandreou on May
26, Cem stressed the need for improving Turkish-Greek ties and
cooperation in various sectors, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency
Tuesday quoted diplomatic sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources, who asked not to be named, said that Turkey and
Greece should work together in combating terrorism, a reference to
Greece's support for Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Cem said that an open Greek condemnation of the PKK and the end
of its support for the terrorist organization were preconditions
for any improvement in bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece should start a dialogue on jointly combating
terrorism and even sign an agreement in this area, Cem added.
</P>
<P>
Cem's letter came in the wake of a crisis over a disputed
Aegean island during which Papandreou called Cem on May 16, saying
that the two sides should not leave room for provocations but
maintain a spirit of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou has been seeking to thaw the tense atmosphere
between Ankara and Athens since he took over as foreign minister
following the dismissal of Theodoros Pangalos over his role in the
Ocalan crisis.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Turkey's Ankara Security Court No. 2 started the
trial of Ocalan on charges of treason on the Imrali Island in
Marmara Sea near Turkey's western province of Bursa.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was arrested by Turkish special agents in Kenya in
mid-February when he left the Greek Embassy in Nairobi, where he
had taken refuge for 12 days after an undisclosed odyssey seeking
asylum in vain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
