<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican President Stresses Peace for Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano said here Tuesday that it is of great importance to
maintain peace and the unity of the nation and the harmony of the
family for the sake of children, without which the children will
have nothing left.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the occasion to mark the International Children's
Day, Chissano said that in the development of agriculture,
industry, communications, mining and tourism, enough attention
should be given to the protection of environment, random felling
of trees and the destruction of soil, water resources and
biological resources and the pollution of air should be banned, so
that the children can live in a pollution-free environment.
</P>
<P>
The president said that environment protection and the
protection of children's security demand the elimination of armed
conflicts, which have ended in environmental pollution, poverty
and hindered the economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the 24 years of progress the country has made in
improving children's condition since Mozambique's independence in
1975, Chissano said that another two million people in the
countryside have got better water supply in the past few years,
and about 35 percent of the whole population now have access to
clean water.
</P>
<P>
To protect children from bad impact from the society, the
parliament has passed a law banning children from going to
entertainment places in the night, and the government has also
taken measures to encourage orphaned or abandoned children to
return home.
</P>
<P>
He said that about 15,000 orphaned or abandoned children have
returned to their homes in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also admitted that there is still a lot to do in
children protection, listing that some conventions on children's
protection are not well observed in the country, and many children
still suffer physically and spiritually from family violences,
AIDS and drugs.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government institutions, non-government
organizations, various organizations, families and other sectors
of the society to care about children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Bulgaria Sign Cooperation Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and Bulgaria Tuesday signed
three agreements on investments, taxes and tourism in a bid to
further boost economic cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Bulgarian Minister of Trade and Tourism Valentin
Vasilev and Lebanese Finance Minister George Korom signed two
agreements on protecting and encouraging investments and avoiding
dual taxation.
</P>
<P>
Vasilev signed another agreement with Lebanese Tourism
Minister Artur Nazarian on cooperation in tourism.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, the Bulgarian minister said he
hoped the agreements would help boost economic ties between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said his country, which is a member of the World Trade
Organization, would like to help Lebanon join the group.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian exports to Lebanon have dropped 48 percent in the
past three years from 48 million U.S. dollars to 30 million
dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Lebanese exports to Bulgaria stood at 2 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Vasilev, who is leading a delegation of about 40 business
leaders on a three-day visit, arrived here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, he has met with Lebanese President Emile
Lahoud, Prime Minister Salim Hoss and House Speaker Nabih Berri.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
