<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Pledges Assistance to Angolan Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Brazilian Foreign Minister
Luis Filipe Lampreia said in Luanda Tuesday that his government
will increase assistance to Angolan development and invest more in
the Angolan petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos,
Lampreia told the press that Brazil will provide assistance for
the water distribution system in capital Luanda and low-income
housing projects.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian foreign minister said that his government is
ready to help establish a big technical training center in Luanda,
where many Angolans will acquire such skills as carpentry, civil
engineering and sewing.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia noted that Brazil is interested in investing in the
petroleum sector. But he did not disclose any details in this
respect.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is a country with poor petroleum reserve. And since
1980s, Petrobras, the state-run national petroleum corporation of
the southern American country has been exploring and exploiting
oil in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian minister said that the debt Angola owes to Brazil
is under technical discussion and meanwhile, Brazil is ready to
release the credit which has been suspended for Angola.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia arrived in Luanda Monday on a two-day visit to the
southern African country. The purpose of his visit is to offer
"political and economic support" for Angola in a bid to help
achieve peace in the war- torn country, Brazilian Ambassador to
Luanda Alexandre Ador Neto said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
