<HEADLINE> Tanzanian-Zambian Railway to Be Commercialized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Zambia have reached an
agreement to commercialize the Tanzanian-Zambian Railways
Authority (TAZARA) in order to revamp the performance of the
1,860- kilometer long railway.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Communications and Transport Minister David Saviye
announced the commercialization plan Tuesday and said the
performance of railway authority is not satisfactory at present.
</P>
<P>
He said discussions are underway with various stakeholders on
the future of the railway, including the possibility of a joint
venture with China, which completed the construction of the
railway in mid-1970s as economic aid to the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have reached consensus on making the railway
market- oriented and commercially viable with privatization or
joint venture approach, he said.
</P>
<P>
The volume of transport of the inter-country railway stood at
550,000 tons in 1997 compared with 1.2 million tons in 1993, while
in 1998 the volume was slightly higher, reaching 639,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The minister also admitted the significant role the railway
has played and will continue to play in enhancing investment,
trade and development in the sub-region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
