<HEADLINE> Yugoslav War a Failure for NATO, Says Former </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The war in Yugoslavia waged by the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) was characterized by
failure and the violation of numerous principles, a former German
official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Oskar Lafontaine, former German finance minister, said at a
book presentation in Athens that the aims of NATO's intervention
had not been attained, given that it had not helped the people of
Kosovo, on the contrary, it had contributed further to their
uprooting, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine, who resigned earlier this year as chairman of
Germany's ruling Social Democrat Party, said that it was not
possible to defend human rights by bombing civilians. The way in
which NATO was acting was unacceptable, he added.
</P>
<P>
They could not make things right if they did not take into
consideration existing international law and did not strengthen
it, the former minister said, adding that the United Nations
Security Council should not be passed over. 
</P>
