<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Peace Core of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli-Palestinian peace is
the essence of the Middle East peace process and Israel's peace
with Syria and Lebanon should not be at the expense of the
Palestinian track, senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I don not think we will allow tracks against tracks. We would
be happy to see Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights and
Lebanese territory, the point is that we want to reach a
comprehensive peace on all tracks," Erekat told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came a day after the pro-Israeli South Lebanon
Army (SLA) began to pull out of the south Lebanon enclave of
Jezzine in a move widely seen as a prelude to a larger-scale
Israeli withdrawal from a buffer zone it carved out in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak has promised during
his successful election campaign that he would withdraw Israeli
troops from south Lebanon within a year through an agreement with
Syria, the real power behind Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants Israel to hand over the Golan Heights it seized in
the 1967 Middle East war. Talks between the two sides broke off
in early 1996, but the Israeli government confirmed Sunday that
the two sides had conducted secret talks through various channels
from mid-1997 to late 1998.
</P>
<P>
In their first talks since the May 17 elections, outgoing
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu briefed Barak Tuesday on these
talks, in which some progress had been reportedly made on
security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are concerned that Barak might devote most of
his attention to the Lebanese and Syrian tracks after his
government begins to operate, thus postponing peacemaking with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian conflict is "the core of the
(Israeli-Arab) problems," Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
The senior Palestinian official also urged Barak to stand up
against the intensified moves by the departing government to
expand Jewish settlements, saying his silence on this issue was
"uncomprehensible."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians worried that Barak, who is trying to form a
broad-based coalition government, might not move firmly to curb
settlement building despite his pledge to revive peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Warning that they will not resume peace negotiations with
Israel without a halt to the settlement activities, Palestinian
officials have called for a "day of Palestinian anger" against
settlement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said he hoped the Palestinians will voice their anger
peacefully in the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Beilin, a senior Labor legislator, called on the
Palestinian National Authority to stop "flaming the passion"
before it was turned into violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
