<HEADLINE> Neighboring Country Leaders Call for Peace in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania, Uganda and Rwanda
agreed Tuesday on the urgency of restoring peace in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
A joint communique issued after a mini-summit here on the DRC
between Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa, Uganda's Yoweri
Museveni and Rwanda's Pasteur Bizimungu, said they deliberated on
steps towards a peaceful solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The day-long summit, which was also attended by Rwanda's
Vice-President and Minister of Defense, Paul Kagame, is an
extension of the one held in central Tanzania's Dodoma town in
early May.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the summit welcomed the commitment made by
the DRC and Uganda towards achieving a peaceful solution to the
conflict which has started since last August.
</P>
<P>
The heads of states also welcomed the unilateral cessation of
hostilities declared by Rwanda, a measure which is intended to
enhance chances of a negotiated and comprehensive ceasefire
agreement within the context of the Lusaka Peace Process.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters after the talks, which lasted about four
hours at the State House, President Mkapa underlined the need for
withdrawal of troops from the DRC by all parties involved in the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa explained that the issue is not just centered on
withdrawal of troops of countries supporting the rebels but also
those bolstering the DRC government.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa added that Tuesday's summit is aimed at working out a
conducive environment through which peace and stability could be
restored in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Chad has withdrawn its troops from the DRC. Uganda began
pulling out of the southwestern part of the mineral-rich country.
On May 28, Rwanda declared a unilateral cease-fire there. All
these constitute a good beginning to the final negotiated
settlement to the conflict.  
</P>
</TEXT>
