<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Falls by a Sharp 2.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department reported
Tuesday that U.S. construction spending plunged by a sharp 2.4
percent in April, the biggest monthly decline in more than 5
years.
</P>
<P>
The Department said the April decline followed five straight
monthly increases including a 1.3 percent gain in March and a
sizable 2.1 percent rise in February. The April decline was the
first setback since a 0.3 percent drop last October and it was the
biggest monthly decrease since a 3 percent drop in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Department's report showed that spending on residential
construction dropped by 1 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 324.7 billion dollars with both single-family homes
and apartments suffering declines.
</P>
<P>
The April's construction spending for all private building
projects was off 1.9 percent as spending on factories, office
buildings, hotels and hospitals all saw declines. Spending on
private construction had been up 1.9 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Spending on government construction projects fell an even
sharper 4.2 percent in April, the largest decline in this category
since a 4.8 percent decrease last May. Public spending had fallen
0.8 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The report said spending for highways, hospitals and water
supply facilities were all down while spending on military
facilities and housing redevelopment recorded increases.
</P>
<P>
For April, spending on all construction projects totaled 697.4
billion dollars at a seasonally adjusted annual rate, up 8 percent
from the spending level in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Construction spending had been one of the driving forces in the
U.S. economic expansion. The sharp drop of 2.4 percent in April
caught analysts by surprise. In the first three months of this
year, home building and other construction activity driven by low
mortgage rates was a key contributing factor to the strong
economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
