<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Inflation May Push Pay Rises Below 3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 1 (Xinhua) - Wage settlements in Britain are set to
dip below the 3 percent mark in the coming months due to falling
inflation, sluggish economic growth and weak company profits.
</P>
<P>
However, the key determinant of pay was still the Retail Price
Index and the current headline rate of 1.6 percent is forecast to
dip to 1.1 percent by the end of the year, according to the pay
analysts Industrial Relations Services (IRS).
</P>
<P>
In a report published Tuesday, IRS says deals in the crucial
April pay round, when most increases take effect, averaged 3
percent for the fourth month in a row despite low unemployment and
the recent introduction of a national minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
Half the pay deals were worth between 2.5 and 3.3 percent, down
from the 2.8 to 3.5 percent range in March and well below
January's 3 to 3.6 percent spread.
</P>
<P>
Analysts at IRS argue that pay settlements will probably follow
falling inflation and "the overall distribution of wage deals may
drift down further in the months ahead".
</P>
<P>
The declining settlements will alleviate the inflationary blip
predicted around the millennium holiday when some employers are
predicted to pay substantial bonuses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
