<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Index Falls 0.1 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The composite index of leading
U.S. economic indicators fell 0.1 percent in April for the first
time since June, 1998, the Conference Board, a prominent research
group, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The group said in a report that the change in direction does
not signal a recession but suggests some softening in the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
"This looks like only a temporary pause, although last week's
drop in the stock market adds some complications," said Michael
Boldin, Director of Business Cycle Research at the Conference
Board. "Still, with most of the leading indicators, including the
stock market, showing increases this year and the economy showing
growth in so many areas, this expansion should continue and become
the longest ever in early 2000."
</P>
<P>
The report said the leading index fell 0.1 percent in April to
107.1, the first decline since June, 1998, when the index dropped
0.2 percent. The March value has been revised down to show no
change and during the six-month span through April, the leading
index rose 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said, six out of the ten of the indicators that make
up the leading index fell in April. The most significant decreases
are vendor performance, average weekly initial claims for state
unemployment insurance and building permits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
