<HEADLINE> NATO Planes Bomb Albanian Bunkers on Border With Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- NATO warplanes dropped bombs about
four kilometers on the Albanian side of the border with Yugoslavia
overnight Tuesday, destroying at least two Albanian government
bunkers and some telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
The bombs created some huge craters on the ground and the
English markings on the shrapnels revealed that it was the work of
NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
sources were quoted as saying that seven bombs were dropped inside
Albania, with one of them bursting just 500 meters from its team.
</P>
<P>
No casualties were reported so far.
</P>
<P>
How NATO planes, which have been striking Yugoslav air-defense
targets in Kosovo near the border, bombed the bunkers was not
known immediately.
</P>
<P>
Fierce fightings have been raging on in nearby hills around the
Morina border crossing over the past week between Yugoslav troops
and the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA).
</P>
<P>
The KLA has been trying to open a new supply corridor from
Albania to Prizren, 30 kilometers from the border.
</P>
<P>
With each day passes, the situation at the Morina border
crossing becomes increasingly tense and dangerous. Albanian
border guards have evacuated from their posts to the nearby
barracks and some are seen standing under big trees.
</P>
<P>
As NATO continues its airstrikes against Yugoslavia, Kosovo
refugees keep pouring into Albania through the crossing.
</P>
<P>
An Albanian newspaper reported Tuesday that a defused NATO bomb
fell into a seaside restaurant in the Albanian port of Durres on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
When the incident occurred, a number of people including some
Italian military policemen were dining in the restaurant, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, Albanian president Rexhep Meidani held an
emergency meeting to review the tense situation on the
northeastern border and discussed the measures which need to be
taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
