<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released by Xinhua today:
</P>
<P>
China, Sierra Leone Summit
</P>
<P>
China and Sierra Leone have had fruitful cooperation in
political, economic, military and other areas, and have supported
and cooperated with each other in international affairs, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin said in a meeting with Sierra Leone's
President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Chinese government encourages enterprises in mutually-
beneficial cooperation with Sierra Leone in various ways and in
exploring new spheres to further promote bilateral ties, he said.
</P>
<P>
China supports the Economic Community of West African States in
trying to restore peace to the country and will continue to push
for international support for the peace process and reconstruction
of Sierra Leone, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Cox Report Criticized
</P>
<P>
Contrary to what the Cox Report says, China has worked entirely
on its own to achieve success in a number of efforts from nuclear
weapons to high-tech research, said Defense Minister Chi Haotian
in a meeting with Chief of the General Staff of the Romanian Armed
Forces Constin Degeratu.
</P>
<P>
China on Kosovo Issue
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit of Yugoslav leader by the United States and a few
NATO nations is but a carefully plotted political scheme aiming at
legalizing their aggressive war against the sovereign state of
Yugoslavia, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said
today.
</P>
<P>
China is ready to enhance consultation with Russia on the
Kosovo issue as the two countries "share similar or identical
views on the problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
China, U.S. Relations
</P>
<P>
Zhu Bangzao today urged the U.S. government to take more
practical and effective measures to exempt the normal Sino-U.S.
scientific and technologic trade from being disturbed.
</P>
<P>
He expressed strong displeasure and resolute opposition on
behalf of the Chinese government over the U.S. Defense
Department's announcement to sell Hell Fire Missiles and advanced
intelligence and electronic equipment to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
China, DPRK Ties
</P>
<P>
The maintaining of friendly relations between China and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) are conducive to
peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific region, said Foreign
Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao.
</P>
<P>
China will contribute its efforts to consolidating and
developing the Sino-DPRK relations, Zhu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
