<HEADLINE> India Offers to Consider Safe Passage for "Infiltrators" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- India on Tuesday offered to
consider a "safe passage" for what it termed as Pakistani
"infiltrators" in the Kargil area in Kashmir for retreating to
their side of the line of control (LOC).
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister George Fernandes Tuesday ruled out any
compromise in the on-going conflict with Pakistan, saying that New
Delhi's position was very clear that all those who had been pushed
into India's territory must go back across the LOC.
</P>
<P>
Asked if India could negotiate a cease-fire or a settlement to
end the border conflict during the planned visit of Pakistani
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz to New Delhi, Fernandes said the
issue of safe passage (for infiltrators) could be considered.
</P>
<P>
An Indian military commander said here Tuesday that Indian
troops, backed by air strikes, intensified their efforts to
isolate intruders in the Kargil sector.
</P>
<P>
Intense fighting was also going on at two places in the Patalik
sector, Brigadier Mohan Bhandari informed reporters here, adding
that Indian troops had made a "steady progress" in the Kargil
sector.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that intelligence reports indicated that the
infiltrators were being given reinforcements from across the LOC.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes said Tuesday the armed conflict between the two
neighbors "may not be a long drawn affair and neither will it be
an easy one."
</P>
<P>
India has agreed to a visit by Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz to defuse what caretaker Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee described as a war-like situation in Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the External Affairs Ministry said Tuesday that
India was yet to receive any specific date from Pakistan for the
visit.
</P>
<P>
"We have received a proposal which we have accepted. But there
is no specific time frame," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
