<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Head Calls for Improved Working Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Head of the International Labor
Organization (ILO) Juan Somavia has urged governments and
employers to improve the lives and working conditions of workers.
</P>
<P>
In his first report to the International Labor Conference which
began here Tuesday, the ILO's new director-general said that "the
primary goal of the ILO today is to promote opportunities for
women and men to obtain decent and productive work, in conditions
of freedom, equity, security and human dignity".
</P>
<P>
Somavia, who took office last March, pledged that his
organization would pursue four strategic objectives: the promotion
of rights at work, employment, social protection, and social
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ILO needs to be concerned with all workers,
including the large majority of the workforce in developing
countries whose efforts to achieve well-being are circumscribed by
the poor wages, low productivity and inadequate social protection
found in informal sector activities, which are gaining ground in
many countries.
</P>
<P>
Somavia said that in addition to seeking improvements in the
conditions of work, the ILO needs to commit itself to expanding
opportunities for employment.
</P>
<P>
"The ILO is, therefore, as much concerned with the unemployed,
and with policies to overcome unemployment and underemployment, as
it is with the promotion of rights at work," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ILO head also called for a new consensus to be forged
between the international community, business and labor to address
the social consequences of globalization.
</P>
<P>
In years to come, he said, the major issue confronting the
international community "will be the adaptation of national
economies and institutions to global change, including the
adaptation of global change to human needs".
</P>
<P>
In view of the economic and social challenges wrought by
globalization, the ILO head said that "the ILO will be called upon
to deal with recurring crises of adjustment and development over
the next decade. It must now organize itself for this purpose".
</P>
<P>
China is among the 174 ILO members present at the 87th session
of the ILO's governing body. The meeting will end on June 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WIPO Launches First Distance Learning Course Over Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Intellectual Property
Organization (WIPO) launched its first distance learning course
over the Internet tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This innovative online teaching technique will bring teachers
specializing in intellectual property issues closer to students
and other interested parties in all corners of the world through
virtual means," said the Geneva-based WIPO in its press release.
</P>
<P>
The method will allow anyone seeking more information about
intellectual property to follow a range of educational programs in
intellectual property at their own pace in their own space, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The course is the first of a series of Internet-based programs
to be developed by the WIPO Worldwide Academy WWA), which is
entirely devoted to teaching and training in intellectual
property.
</P>
<P>
Teaching will take place in the virtual environment of the WWA
website, http://academy.wipo.int. A network of tutors has been
established in various regions of the world to support students
during their work. Students and teachers can interact as often as
necessary during the course.
</P>
<P>
"Distance should no longer be an obstruction to instruction,"
said WIPO Director-General Kamil Idris. "The academy's distance
learning initiative will enable students anywhere in the world to
learn about the basics of intellectual property. We hope this
program will flourish to include more advanced courses in the near
future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
