<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militia Starts Withdrawal Amid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Amid heavy attacks by Lebanese
guerrillas, the pro-Israeli militia South Lebanon Army (SLA)
Tuesday started a pullout from Jezzine in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The SLA militiamen knocked down earth mounds and dynamited
fortified positions in and around Jezzine, just north of the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Truck convoys were also seen streaming out of the beleaguered
town, carrying artillery and motor guns, equipment, ammunition and
household furniture to the Israeli self-declared security zone
which it set up in 1985 to shield its northern flank from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
But, the pullout was accompanied by intensified attacks by
Hezbollah, or Party of God, in which two roadside bombs killed two
SLA militiamen and wounded another on Tuesday in Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
Israeli jets staged dozens of bombing sorties against suspected
Hezbollah strongholds near Jezzine as an air cover for its ally's
smooth pullout.
</P>
<P>
During the air raids, three Syrian workers were wounded in
Iqlim Toufah, north of the occupied zone, security sources said.
</P>
<P>
Despite SLA's declaration that the pullout occurs on Tuesday
and ends by mid-June, most residents in Jezzine expect the
withdrawal to be conducted in two stages and to be completed by
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The first stage involves the militia redeploying in Jezzine
from nearby strongholds and the second stage will see the militia
withdrawing to the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said SLA has abandoned strongholds in Roum,
Homsiyah, Azour and Qaitolieh around Jezzine and barricaded
itself inside the town.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong militia decided to leave the area as it
suffered many casualties in the past, according to the SLA's
commander Gen. Antoine Lahd, who formally announced the
withdrawal plan in a news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 SLA fighters have been killed and about 400
others wounded in attacks by Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Lahd warned that the area not be used by Hezbollah as a base,
corridor or launching pad for attacks on Israelis in south
Lebanon, hoping Lebanese authorities would send troops to
Jezzine to protect local residents.
</P>
<P>
But, it is not immediately clear whether the Lebanese army
would take over Jezzine after the SLA departure.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government has been reluctant to commit regular
troops to Jezzine lest this is interpreted as providing security
guarantees for Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Prime Minister Salim Hoss said the government would take
full responsibility for the security and safety of the remaining
5,000 residents in the town after the end of SLA's 14-year
reign.
</P>
<P>
The SLA is trained and financed by Israel to help it patrol
the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
Its members are considered as traitors in Lebanon and Lahd has
been sentenced to death in absentia by a military court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
