<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: NATO Won't Compromise on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said on Tuesday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) will not compromise on its demand that the alliance be "at
the core" of any security force that enters Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"By being at the core, that means there must be a command and
control structure that is NATO's in charge of any peacekeeping
operation," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after addressing a suburban Washington
high school, Cohen said that NATO is planning to put as many as
50,000 armed troops in a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
But Cohen reiterated that it would enter Kosovo only after
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic gives up fighting ethnic
Albanian rebels and withdraws his troops.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also ruled out a pause in the bombing campaign, as
demanded in a letter delivered from Belgrade to German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer in which Yugoslav officials said they
accepted NATO's principals for a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that Belgrade will accept "a United Nations
presence, mandate and other elements to be decided by a U.N.
Security Council resolution in accordance with the United Nations
charter."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the bombing would stop only when Milosevic accepted
all of NATO's main demands, including the return of hundreds of
thousands of ethnic Albanians refugees, and withdrawal of his
troops to demonstrate his acceptance of peace.
</P>
<P>
"A pause would only serve Milosevic's interests," Cohen said.
"He is seeking to try to divide the alliance. He's seeking delay.
We are now at the point where the air campaign is being
intensified on a 24-hour basis."
</P>
<P>
Greece, Italy and other European countries have also proposed
such a pause in the alliance's bombing to give peace a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
