<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End in  Mixed Mode </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- European bourses closed mainly in
the red Tuesday with London the only major market to resist the
selling pressures from Wall Street as its blue chips ended the
session in the black.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 closed 23.8 points higher at 6250 a gain of 0.38
percent, having been at one stage up more than 100 points at
6354.3.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts warned that relatively thin trading had
accentuated some of the gains as worries over the next move in
U.S. interest rates sent Wall Street sharply lower.
</P>
<P>
A stronger-than-expected U.S. National Association of
Purchasing Management report weighed on U.S. shares and took the
shine off the London market.
</P>
<P>
Other European markets, which had traded weakly throughout the
session, succumbed much earlier to Wall Street's early losses.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt was the biggest loser among the main
bourses, ending the session almost 58 points lower, a fall of 1.14
percent, at 5010.71.
</P>
<P>
The Germany's largest retailer, Metro, felt the brunt of an
analyst downgrade from buy to hold, with the stock losing almost 3
percent to close at 59 euros.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 in Paris ended 0.86 percent lower on the day, as it
shed 38 points to close at 4313.69. 
</P>
</TEXT>
