<HEADLINE> UNDP, EC Join Hands to Preserve Forests in 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) and the European Commission (EC) have
launched a joint initiative to strengthen sustainable forestry
management and to support sustainable livelihood programs in
Cameroon, Guyana and Malawi, UNDP officials said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP's Sustainable Energy and Environment Division (SEED)
is expected to begin soon activities under the new collaboration,
in which EC will commit 2.06 million U.S. dollars to the joint
effort, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, which will be administered through UNDP's
Program on Forests (PROFOR), will make an important contribution
to preserving forests and to promoting the sustainable use of
forests resources by consolidating existing efforts and designing
national programs that both protect forests and fight poverty
through sustainable livelihood strategies.
</P>
<P>
In Cameroon, the program will strengthen national capacities in
sustainable forestry management and will create a mechanism to
coordinate and exchange information on forestry and sustainable
and economically viable use of the country's forestry resources.
</P>
<P>
In Malawi, the effort will respond to locally identified
priorities, such as the need for innovative finance mechanisms,
capacity building, support for planning mechanisms and the
development of key indicators needed for policy formulation.
</P>
<P>
The initiative forms a strategic alliance between the UNDP and
the EC that underscores the high priority given to forestry
issues by both organizations.
</P>
<P>
UNDP's Program on Forests builds on the recommendations of the
Commission on Sustainable Development's Intergovernmental Panel on
Forests and works at both national and international levels to
advance sustainable forest management.
</P>
<P>
The program develops and tests innovative approaches such as
private-public partnerships that provide sustainable livelihoods
for people dependent on forestry resources.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP/EC partnership will contribute to the development
cooperation goals of the EC in the areas of forestry and
biodiversity conservation, as well as in capacity building for
improved forestry management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Export Diversification in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank on Tuesday
announced the approval of a credit totaling 32 million U.S.
dollars for the Bangladesh Export Diversification project that
will help the South Asian country expand the range, depth, and
quantity of exports.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in a statement that the project will help speed
Bangladesh's integration into the world economy by giving the
country's entrepreneurs the know-how they need to gain greater
access to world markets and by making public policies and
institutions more supportive to export needs.
</P>
<P>
The project supports the government of Bangladesh's efforts to
overcome a number of market failures that keep the country's
exporters from realizing their full comparative advantage in the
international marketplace, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The project will provide technical assistance to entrepreneurs
for business planning, product development, and researching new
markets and it will help develop private in-country export support
services.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the project will focus on removing the policy and
institutional constraints on export development and on building
the government's capacity to manage and support trade.
</P>
<P>
To encourage export firms to take the fullest possible
advantage of local and foreign business development services, the
project will establish a Matching Grant Facility. The
12-million-dollar facility is a temporary instrument to actively
encourage the use of business support services to enhance firms'
export capability by providing grants covering 50 percent of the
cost of service fees and associated travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
The project also aims to improve the business environment for
industry and commerce through reforms in trade policy and the
first phase of Customs administration reform. These reforms will
reduce costs now imposed by policy, procedural, and
infrastructure-related impediments.
</P>
<P>
The interest-free credit is provided by the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary
lending arm, on standard IDA terms with 40 years to maturity and a
10-year grace period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IT Market in China Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China's information technology
(IT) market will be valued at 15 billion U.S. dollars by 2000,
when the country is expected to become the largest IT market in
the Asia-Pacific region excluding Japan, said a report released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report by U.S. market research firm
International Data Corporation (IDC), China is the fastest growing
IT market in Asia with a 1998-2003 compound annual growth rate of
27.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, IDC said, the overall IT market in China reached 9.24
billion U.S. dollars, which enabled China's IT market to surpass
South Korea and become the second largest in the Asia-Pacific
region (excluding Japan). IDC expects China to pull ahead of
Australia and become the largest IT market in the region by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Although China experienced low growth in the last five years,
IDC said, by 2003 the country is expected to represent
approximately one-third of the total IT market in the Asia-Pacific
region, excluding Japan.
</P>
<P>
While hardware tends to overshadow other segments of the
market, IDC said that there has been strong growth in the data
communications equipment, package software and IT services areas.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, hardware accounted for almost 86 percent of China's
total IT market, according to IDC. Data communications equipment,
which represented 8.2 percent of the market, reached 1.175 billion
U.S. dollars, an increase of almost 41 percent over the previous
year, while IT services experienced an increase of 50 percent and
accounted for 5.9 percent of the total market.
</P>
<P>
Finance continued to be the largest vertical industry in China,
accounting for 32.2 percent of total IT spending. This was
followed by telecom and transportation at 18.1 percent and 10.1
percent, respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
