<HEADLINE> Ghana Hikes Petroleum Prices by 15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ghana Tuesday announced a
15-percent average increase in prices of petroleum products with
immediate effect, the Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Acting General Manager of the state-run Bulk Oil Storage and
Transport, Kwabena Donkor, said in Accra that the adjustment was
in conformity with price change on the world market and the
country's policy of "import parity" .
</P>
<P>
Donkor said that by April this year, prices of crude oil on the
world market had risen to 15.3 U.S. dollars from 12.64 dollars
last October.
</P>
<P>
The increases now peg ex-pump prices of a liter of premium
petrol at 855. 56 cedis up from 744.44 cedis per liter previously.
 Similarly, a liter of kerosene has shot up to 600 cedis while gas
oil has moved to 822.23 cedis a liter. Liquefied petroleum gas
(LPG) is now sold at 920 cedis per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
On future price adjustment, Donkor said, his company will
review prices on monthly basis to determine the ex-depot
wholesale prices of petroleum products for supply to the oil
marketing companies.
</P>
<P>
The company has adjusted petroleum prices twice downwards
between February, 1997 and October, 1998. (one U.S. dollar equals
2,422 cedis) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
