<HEADLINE> DRC Conflict Focus of SADC Meeting in Lusaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The conflict in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) would be the focus of a regional meeting
in Lusaka on June 26, South African President Nelson Mandela and
his Namibian counterpart, Sam Nujoma, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They told reporters in Pretoria that the meeting of member
states of the Southern African Development Community, to be
chaired by Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, was aimed at
declaring a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that we are moving toward finding a peaceful solution
in the DRC," Nujoma said.
</P>
<P>
He said a draft cease-fire agreement had been drawn up with
input from the secretary-general of the Organization of African
Unity, Salim Ahmed Salim, and a special representative of the
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said it was difficult to say how long after the meeting
a resolution would be achieved, "but we hope soon".
</P>
<P>
Both presidents said they were confident that efforts to seek
peace in the DRC were starting to bear fruit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
