<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Assists Water Sector Reform in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank on Tuesday
approved a loan of 30 million U.S. dollars for Argentina to
support water sector reform in medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the project is to support water sector reform
in cities with populations of about 50,000 to 500,000 by
introducing private sector participation in the operation and
management of water utilities, adopting appropriate regulatory
frameworks, and institutionalizing tariff policies and tested
investment alternatives to better reach poor consumers, the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
The reform process expects to put this segment of Argentina's
water and sanitation sector on a sound enough footing to attract
private sector financing, combined with an appropriate role for
the public sector.
</P>
<P>
The loan is on the bank's standard terms for LIBOR-based, U.S.
dollar, single-currency loans, with a maturity of 15 years and
grace period of five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
