<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Researchers Urged to Tackle Cassava </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's Deputy Minister of Food and
 Agriculture, J. Asiedu Nketiah, Tuesday urged African researchers
to examine major constraints to strategic planning for developing
cassava as an important food and cash crop.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister made the call at a three-day workshop on
the development of cassava in west and central Africa held in
Accra, the Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Nketiah identified some of the constraints as lack of improved
varieties to replace local types, poor husbandry practices,
unavailability of planting materials due to low multiplication
ratio. The crop is also bulky and perishable.
</P>
<P>
Other problems are lack of appropriate planting and harvesting
technology to attract medium- and large-scale farmers, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Ghanaian official also called for close collaboration and
coordination of research efforts among international agricultural
research centers and national research and extension systems to
tackle the problems.
</P>
<P>
He noted that cassava, a national diet in many African
countries, has been the main source of many nutrients. It is
produced under various agro- ecological conditions some of which
are unsuitable for many other crops.
</P>
<P>
Africa alone produces 42 percent of the world's cassava, using
principally subsistence agriculture on 10.5 million hectares on
the most marginal lands of the tropics and sub-tropics in 41
countries.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, organized by the United Nations World Food
Organization in collaboration with the International Fund for
Agriculture, is being attended by agriculture researchers from 12
African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
