<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Italy Stress NATO Conditions for Bombing Pause </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Tuesday met Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini as part of a series of meetings with allied leaders aimed at
demonstrate allied unity on NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
The allies differ on the ground troops deployment, a pause in
the bombing campaign against Yugoslavia and targeting of the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign Minister Dini and I... remain committed to concluding
the conflict on the basis of the conditions NATO set and the
international community endorsed," Albright told a joint press
conference.
</P>
<P>
She reiterated that the Serb forces must leave Kosovo so that
the refugees and displaced persons may return safely to their
homes, and an international military presence with NATO at its
core must be established.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of the relationships of the G-8, but as a condition
for the suspension of bombing, the NATO five conditions are what
stand," she noted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of a pause in the bombing, Dini stressed the same
conditions as Albright did, saying that Belgrade must meet all the
five conditions and the G-8 principles.
</P>
<P>
"If this is not accepted and is not verifiable, then I do not
think that it will be possible for the Alliance to come to
agreement on the suspension of bombing," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its allies have given Finnish President
Martti Ahtisaari a detailed plan for Kosovo to put to Belgrade if
he goes on Wednesday, the U.S. State Department said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The plan should enable Ahtisaari, the European Union's Balkan
envoy, to answer any Yugoslav questions such as when an
international peace force would deploy in the province and who
would verify a Yugoslav withdrawal so that NATO bombing can stop,
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart also seeks
clarification on how far Yugoslavia was willing to go to satisfy
NATO demands for ending the war over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeking some further clarification," the spokesman
said. "The work that's being done is to understand exactly what
it is that the authorities in Belgrade say they are willing to
agree to."
</P>
<P>
In a letter delivered from Belgrade to German Foreign Minister
Joschka Fischer, Yugoslav officials said they accepted NATO's
principles for a peace settlement and asked for a pause in the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that Belgrade will accept "a United Nations
presence, mandate and other elements to be decided by a U.N.
Security Council resolution in accordance with the United Nations
charter." 
</P>
</TEXT>
