<HEADLINE> Sierra Leonean Rebels Block ECOMOG Supplying Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean rebels Tuesday blocked
a highway serving as a supply route for the west African
peace-keeping force ECOMOG, threatening to undermine a
hardly-earned cease-fire, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The road blocks are at Okra Hill, about 60 kilometers from
Sierra Leonean capital Freetown, which is used by the ECOMOG force
backing the government to provide supplies for its troops in the
country's interior areas.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are guarding their blocks with heavy machine guns,
an ECOMOG spokesman was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We have complained to the U.N. Observer Mission in Sierra
Leone and we are waiting patiently to get the rebels to clear the
road blocks," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the ECOMOG may strike in the next few days if
this fails.
</P>
<P>
U.N. sources said their mission was in contact with the rebels
and the rebels have promised to clear the road blocks within 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire taking effect on May 24 in a bid to nurture
atmosphere for peace talks held in Togo has been largely
respected, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The talks, jointly brokered by the Economic Community of West
Africa States (ECOWAS) and the United Nations, have made some
progress though the thorny dispute on a transitional government
remains.
</P>
<P>
The rebels suggest that they must share power with President
Tejan Kabbah in a transitional government until a new election is
held, while President Kabbah insists that the rebels must
transform into a political party and compete in the general
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
