<HEADLINE> Global Equity Holdings Grow 23 Percent in 1998: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Global institutional equity
holdings grew 23 percent in 1998 to a value of 14.9 trillion U.S.
dollars, exceeding the 18 percent growth rate a year earlier, a
leading U.S. information company said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the 1999 International Target Cities Report, the New
York-based Thomson Financial Investor Relations said London and
New York led the top 5 cities in the world, with each city
controlling over 2.0 trillion dollars in equity.
</P>
<P>
They were followed by Boston, Tokyo and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the value of U.S. managers' equity holdings rose
25.3 percent to 8.0 trillion dollars with the U.S. market up 26.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
European managers' equity holdings rose 17 percent to 5.0
trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report found that U.S. investors appeared to have moved
funds into Latin and Asian equities, "despite or perhaps because of
weak conditions in those markets", and to have scaled down their
investment in core European markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
