<HEADLINE> Russian, EU Envoys Agree on Peace Plan for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Balkans envoys from Russia and the
European Union and senior official from the United States cleared
their eleventh-hour differences over a peace plan to present to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The envoys, former Russian premier Viktor Chernomyrdin and
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, were ready to depart for
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said NATO and Russia would send troops to Kosovo
as part of a peacekeeping presence with the United Nations'
approval and support.
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO and Yugoslavia would have to hammer out a
document on the withdrawal of Yugoslav troops from Kosovo so that
NATO would end its bombing.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment, there is a realistic chance the war will end,"
Chernomyrdin told reporters. "I think it is now realistic to stop
the bombing of Yugoslavia and this is what I am taking to Belgrade.
"
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during talks near Bonn among
Chernomyrdin, his EU counterpart and Finnish President Ahtisaari
and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
One major distinction during the negotiations has been the
composition of a peacekeeping force to be deployed in Yugoslavia
after the bombing ends.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari delayed their planned visit
to Belgrade when Talbott introduced several new proposals during
the preparatory talks before the Belgrade trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
