<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SW Chinese Province Sets Up 42 Protected Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China's southwestern province of
Guizhou is taking a lead in establishing separate zones for
protecting forests and wild life.
</P>
<P>
The province, which boasts rich animal and plant resources, has
set up 42 protected zones, of which seven have national status
classification.
</P>
<P>
"The zones, covering a total space of 29 million square
kilometers, provide good living environments for endangered
species," experts say.
</P>
<P>
To manage the zones, the province has set up a special unit of
over 500 full-time employees and 400 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the province has also legislated to better
protect wild life.  
</P>
</TEXT>
