<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- At least nine people were killed as an American
Airlines flight with 145 people aboard skidded off a rain-slicken
runway, broke apart and burst into flames in Arkansas State of the
United States before midnight Tuesday, the Associated Press (AP)
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 people were injured and taken to hospitals, and 14 were
not immediately accounted for. Fifty-one others did not require
hospital treatment.
</P>
<P>
Flight 1420, a Super MD-80, had 139 passengers and six crew
members and was due to arrive in Little Rock City at 9:41 p.m.(
local time). The flight from Dallas of Texas State was delayed
for more than two hours and arrived just as the storm was hitting
the city with lightning, hail and winds gusting to nearly 90 mph (
145 kph).(US-Crash Landing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The government of Pakistan-administered Kashmir
was forced to close all educational institutions located near the
Pakistani side of the Line of Control (LoC) in the disputed
Kashmir region.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Pakistan-administered Kashmir told the media
that the educational institutions near the LoC were closed "
because of the deliberate targeting of schools by the Indian army.
"
</P>
<P>
"Other than being an inhuman act, the firing on the civil
population is also against the U.N. Charter," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a result of Indian firing, ten students from
eight to ten years of age were killed in Nagdar in the Neelum
Valley Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Three students of the same ages were also killed in Narr School
in Kotli district Wednesday, the spokesman said, adding that a
large number of students were critically injured because of this
deliberate shelling on schools. (Pakistan-Kashmir-Schools)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The Balkans envoys from Russia and the European Union
and senior official from the United States cleared their eleventh-
hour differences over a peace plan to present to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The envoys, former Russian premier Viktor Chernomyrdin and
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, were ready to depart for
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said NATO and Russia would send troops to Kosovo
as part of a peacekeeping presence with the United Nations'
approval and support.
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO and Yugoslavia would have to hammer out a
document on the withdrawal of Yugoslav troops from Kosovo so that
NATO would end its bombing.(Russia-EU-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will announce
Wednesday that the United States is to send 7,000 U.S. ground
troops to Kosovo as part of a peacekeeping force of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
White House officials said that Clinton will make the
announcement during his commencement address at the U.S. Air Force
Academy in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had planned to send 4,000 troops to the Yugoslav
province as part of a 28,000 force "with NATO at its core," but it
decided to send more after NATO increased the number to 5,0000.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, the West and Russia settled last-minute
differences over a Kosovo peace plan that Moscow's Balkan envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin said provided a "realistic chance" for ending
the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said in Bonn both NATO and Russia would send
troops under their own respective command to Kosovo as part of a
peace-keeping operation under United Nations auspices. (US-Kosovo-
Troops) 
</P>
</TEXT>
