<HEADLINE> Pak Army Rules Out Evacuation of Civilian from LoC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has ruled out the
possibility of evacuation of the civilian population living in the
areas close to the Line of Control (LoC) in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"Evacuation is not required at all," as the local residents are
used to face sniper and indiscriminate firing from the Indian
side, and they are not prepared to leave their homes under any
circumstances, a Pakistani Army spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brig. Rashid Qureshi, director general of the Inter Service
Public Relations, said at a news briefing that the morale of the
defenseless civilians is very high and they are prepared to face
any eventuality.
</P>
<P>
"Come what may, there will be no evacuation," Qureshi said,
adding that women and children may migrate to safer places, but
men will stay at their homes in any case.
</P>
<P>
He referred to a tragic incident which took place on Tuesday
morning, in which seven school children were killed and three
others wounded as a result of Indian artillery and mortar shelling
on a boys school across the LoC in Keran sector.
</P>
<P>
On the protection of the civilian population, Kashmir Affairs
Minister Majeed Malik said on the occasion that the government has
decided to build concrete bunkers along the LoC for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Indian army has stepped up shelling along the
LoC and targeted civilians, killing innocent people.
</P>
<P>
He assured that the government would provide all possible
protection to the civilians and extend financial help to them. The
government, he added, also set up camps and clinics to help the
displaced persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
