<HEADLINE> Pak Condemns Children Killing By Indian Shelling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Wednesday condemned
the killing of three more school children by Indian shelling.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly condemned this attempt to target civilian
facilities," said Rafiq Altaf, spokesman for the Foreign Office.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports, a mortar shell hit a school
once again Wednesday morning in Pakistan-controlled Kashmir when
three children were killed and four others injured.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had claimed that seven school children were killed by
Indian troops' shelling on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"What is worse, the Indian side denied this crime," said Altaf,
adding that Pakistan will provide documentary evidence for the
killings.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed the claim that the killings were made "by
mistake." "Targeting schools twice in a row is not a mistake," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated that Pakistan is committed to defusing
the tension in Kashmir, while stressing that his country will
"make all efforts" to defend its sovereignty and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to defuse the situation and our peace initiative
and gesture has been highly appreciated by the media," he said,
referring to Pakistan's offer to send its Foreign Minister Sartaj
Aziz to New Delhi for talks on the situation in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The exact date of the proposed visit has yet to be decided,
according to Altaf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
