<HEADLINE> Russian, EU Envoys Delay Belgrade Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) mediator on Kosovo
and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and his Russian partner
Viktor Chernomyrdin Wednesday delayed their planned visit to
Belgrade and remained here to confer with U.S. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott in a bid to find common ground on the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin's spokesman Valentin Sergeyev said Talbott had
suggested several new proposals that "were not mentioned earlier."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was reportedly still meeting with Ahtisaari and
Talbott. It would be decided after their talks whether Ahtisaari
and Chernomyrdin would fly together to the Yugoslav capital on
Wednesday, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said the three mediators talked long into the
night in an effort to coordinate the EU's, Russia's and the U.S.'s
stands on the Kosovo crisis but failed to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Talbott told reporters on Tuesday night that the United States'
position on the crisis had not changed.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the failure to iron out the differences between
the three negotiating parties had led to the delay of the Belgrade
trip.
</P>
<P>
The major difference between Russia and the United States
reportedly lies in the fact that the U.S. insists on Belgrade's
withdrawal of troops from Kosovo as the precondition for a halt to
bombing while Russia could not accept it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
