<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek PM Calls for More Peace Efforts in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
on Wednesday urged that more steps be taken to reach a peaceful
solution to the current crisis over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In an airport statement before his departure for Cologne,
Germany, to attend the European Union (EU) summit which opens
Thursday, Simitis said the peace initiative by the seven Western
countries and Russia for a solution to the Yugoslav crisis was in
progress.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the peace process would fall into line and more steps
would be made in that direction.
</P>
<P>
"We will insist on an agreement as soon as possible," the
premier stressed.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek government spokesman Yiannis
Nikolaou confirmed Wednesday that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright had called her Greek counterpart George
Papandreou n Sunday night and requested communication with
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
He said that Papandreou also contacted Serbian President Milan
Milutinovic and Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic who
expressed the view that a solution was possible based on the peace
proposal by the seven Western countries and Russia, known as the
Group of Eight.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Greece discerned a "positive direction
and preconditions" for a solution to the Yugoslav crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Greece (KKE) Secretary-General Aleka
Papariga warned Wednesday that the Balkan region had entered a
period in which "peace at gunpoint" would alternate with a "real
war." 
</P>
</TEXT>
