<HEADLINE> Cyprus Denies Help to Turkish Rebel Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Wednesday categorically
dismissed reports that it had helped the Turkish outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
"The Cyprus Republic is innocent of any accusation Mr Ocalan is
reported to have made," Cyprus' Government Spokesman Costas
Serezis said.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkish media, the Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan, who is being tried in Turkey, told the Court that the PKK
had received help from Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Ankara Security Court No. 2 on Monday started the
trial of Ocalan on charges of treason on the Imrali Island near
Turkey's western province of Bursa.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions by the presiding judge of the trial,
Ocalan listed Syria, Greece, Cyprus, Iran, Iraq, Yugoslavia,
Armenia, Britain, Greek Orthodox Church and some others as
countries or organizations that had help the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Serezis said, "Ocalan's reported allegations may be related to
possible activity by individuals."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday the Primate of the Greek Orthodox Church of
Cyprus Archbishop Chrysostomos also dismissed claims that the
Cyprus Church had offered financial assistance to the PKK.
</P>
<P>
He said he was "surprised to hear this report, because nothing
of the kind had even happened".
</P>
<P>
The PKK, led by Ocalan, has been fighting a 15-year-long war
for an independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey, which has
claimed over 37,000 lives since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
