<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK District Council Electoral Procedure Spelt Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Electoral Affairs
Commission has laid down a regulation on the procedure for the
District Councils election in November.
</P>
<P>
This includes the publication of a voter register, the
nomination of candidates, polling arrangements and the counting of
ballots.
</P>
<P>
Justice Woo Kwok-hing, chairman of the commission, said at a
press conference Wednesday: "Voting will be made simpler. Chops
bearing the mark of a 'tick' will be provided at every polling
station for electors to mark their ballot paper."
</P>
<P>
"Just use the chop to stamp a 'tick' in the circle opposite the
name of the candidate of your choice" instead of using a pen or
other means to mark the ballot. Otherwise, the vote will be
invalid, he said.
</P>
<P>
In light of public concern about the privacy of personal data,
he said only the name, address and constituency of an elector will
be published for public inspection. Their identity card number and
sex will not be made public, he said.
</P>
<P>
The regulation was drawn up after the commission considered all
the public views received during a public consultation exercise on
its proposed electoral guidelines between April 12 and May 11.
</P>
<P>
A total of 28 written representations were received and 15
persons addressed the commission at a public forum.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines will be finalized after the regulation goes
through the Legislative Council and will be issued in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
