<HEADLINE> Home-made Destroyer Added to Indian Navy Fleet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A home-made destroyer, INS
Mysore, joined the Indian Navy fleet Wednesday at a navy dockyard
in Mumbai, 1400 km southwest of here.
</P>
<P>
Indian caretaker Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee
commissioned the guided missile destroyer, the Press Trust of
India reported.
</P>
<P>
The 5,700 ton warship is the second of India's "Project 17"
series of destroyers of which INS Delhi was commissioned in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The ship is powered by four gas turbines with a total thrust of
64,000 horse power and a top speed of over 42 knots.
</P>
<P>
On its board are 16 surface-to-surface missiles, a battery of
surface-to-air missiles, a 100 mm gun, torpedoes, anti-submarine
rockets and chaff decoys in addition to two seeking helicopters
and advanced radar and electronic warfare equipment.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said at the ceremony that the day was not far when the
entire Indian Navy fleet would comprise indigenously built
warships.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government had sanctioned construction of three next
generation world class frigates, two submarines and an aircraft
carrier.
</P>
<P>
The destroyer was named after another ship, INS Mysore, which
was decommissioned in August 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
