<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Help Train Lesotho Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean troops will join
the South African and Botswana officers in Lesotho to train
Lesotho soldiers under a Southern African Development Community
(SADC) initiative.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili
in the National Assembly Wednesday, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on the status of SADC troops in Lesotho,
Mosisili said the initial Operation Boleas, carried out to
intervene militarily to restore order in Lesotho during the
political crisis last year, has been completed.
</P>
<P>
South African and Botswana troops, who entered Lesotho last
September under the auspices of SADC, completely withdrew from the
mountain kingdom in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The SADC forces have now entered Lesotho with the purpose of
training and developing the Lesotho Defense Force, said Mosisili.
</P>
<P>
He said the responsibility of the security in Lesotho has now
returned to the Lesotho army as the SADC forces have withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
He said the training program to be conducted by SADC forces
would include the examination of the entire Lesotho army to
eliminate redundant officers and also undertake re-training of the
forces.
</P>
<P>
The SADC plan would include the training of new recruits.
</P>
</TEXT>
