<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Regions May Have Flash Floods This Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Meteorologists here on Wednesday
forecast the possibility of flash floods in the northeastern and
southeastern regions of Bangladesh during the current month.
</P>
<P>
The meteorologists, who made the forecast at a regular meeting
of experts of the Bangladesh Meteorological Department, also
predicted the formation of one or two monsoon depressions over the
Bay of Bengal in June which would bring lots of rain over the
country.
</P>
<P>
A bulletin of the department said that moderately heavy to
heavy rainfalls may occur at places over the southeastern and
northeastern parts of the country during the next week, and light
to moderate rain and thundershowers accompanied by gusty and
squally wind may occur over other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall activity is likely to increase at the end of the week,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a bulletin of the Flood Information Center said
light to heavy rainfall at some places over the Brahmaputra and
the Ganges basins, and moderately heavy to heavy rainfall at all
places over the Meghna basin were recorded during the past 24
hours ending at 9:00 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the rivers in the Brahmaputra and the Ganges basins
registered rise while the rivers in the Meghna basin recorded rise
and fall, and all the rivers in the southeastern hill basin
observed fall.
</P>
<P>
The monsoon season begins in the South Asian nation in June
every year, often with heavy rains resulting in floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Nuclear Scientists Refute Cox Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Cox Report dished out by the U.
S. Congress is, in the eyes of Chinese nuclear scientists who have
participated in developing China's nuclear weapons, "nothing but
rumors fabricated out of thin air and brazen lies".
</P>
<P>
Dong Ying, 66, an expert in nuclear fuel, still has a clear
memory of the creative work of Chinese scientists in developing
nuclear weapons in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
"The United States imposed strict sanctions upon New China (
founded in 1949), and experts from the former Soviet Union, who
were then partners of Chinese scientists, were called back
overnight," Dong said, "All of us became strong immediately and
determined to bring credit to the Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
China independently developed and manufactured its own nuclear
weapons arsenal of atomic bombs and H-bombs within that very
special climate.
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of fact, it was impossible and unnecessary for
Chinese scientists to have 'stolen' the U.S. technology of the
1950s to develop missiles, as the Cox Report tried to charge,"
Dong said, shaking with anger.
</P>
<P>
Yu Min, 73, an academician of China's top natural sciences
research body of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), said that
China decided at the very beginning to develop its own nuclear
weapons by its own efforts.
</P>
<P>
China's first atomic bomb was detonated in 1964, followed by
the creation of its first H-bomb two years later.
</P>
<P>
"China has created a world record in terms of its speed in
developing the bombs," said Yu, who is also a research fellow with
the Chinese Academy of Engineering Physics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Nuclear Scientists Refute Cox Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese scientists see the Cox Report as an open slander
against Chinese scientists and other Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"It indeed devalues our capability and our devotion to our
careers and country," Dong said, "I believe U.S. scientists who
are honest and trust the facts would not deny this."
</P>
<P>
Yu noted that Chinese scientists gained their surprising
achievements over four decades by entirely employing their wisdom,
unity, and devotion to their motherland.
</P>
<P>
"It was naturally obvious that we would reach the current level
of development in our nuclear industry since the overall national
strength of China has been increasing after more than two decades
of the reform and opening up drive," Yu said.
</P>
<P>
"What we've achieved reflects the wisdom of the Chinese nation
and its spirit of self-dependence," he said, "It is very strange
that the United States would 'chase the wind and clutch at
shadows', meaning to speak or act on hearsay evidence, when it got
to know what level we are at now."
</P>
<P>
Yu pointed out that the arrogance and hegemonism of the United
States were again exposed to the public. It also showed that some
politicians in the United States were deliberately ruining Sino-U.
S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Renkai, a bi-academician of the CAS and the Chinese
Academy of Engineering (CAE), said that the reason China developed
advanced national defense technology was to safeguard national
security and world peace.
</P>
<P>
"The lesson we must bear in mind is that one could come under
attack if it was less developed," said Zhao, an expert in nuclear
submarines.
</P>
<P>
On whether the normal exchanges between Chinese and U.S.
scientists would be affected, Zhao said that it might have some
temporary impact, but people who were true scientific researchers
would not believe the groundless lies.
</P>
<P>
"The basic understanding is that exchanges benefit the overall
development of human beings," Zhao said, "And lies never last long.
"  
</P>
</TEXT>
