<HEADLINE> Singapore Parliamentarian Resigns Over Fraud Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 2 (Xinhua)-- Singapore Parliamentarian Choo Wee
Khiang resigned after pleading guilty to a cheating charge, the
Office of the Clerk of Parliament announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Choo, representing the constituency of Jalan Besar, had been
charged with assisting another man, said to be a close family
friend of him, to cheat a finance company 830,000 Singapore
dollars (about 488,235 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The judge has mitigated the charge from aggravated to simple
cheating and will make the sentence next Monday.
</P>
<P>
A court official said that Choo had taken a wrong turn, and
that he and the man could have easily obtained financing in a
proper way through a mortgage loan, if they had consulted a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament's announcement said Choo, first elected as an MP
in 1988, submitted earlier Wednesday his resignation letter to the
Speaker.
</P>
<P>
"Choo therefore ceases to be an elected Member of Parliament
from the time of receipt of his letter," said the statement.
</P>
