<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has announced its gross domestic product grew
by only 0.6 percent in 1998, a drop of 1.5 percent compared with
1997.
</P>
<P>
In a note addressed to the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
published in Wednesday's local press, the Jordanian government
said the drop in economic activities particularly centered in the
agricultural and construction sectors.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- An Omani-Yemeni commercial bank will soon be opened
in Sanaa, with the Omani side contributing 30 percent of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" quoted the deputy chairman of
the Yemeni Chamber of Commerce and Industry Mohamed Hassan Al
Zobeiri, who is currently visiting Oman, as saying the opening of
the bank will crown bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He indicated the two countries were contemplating the
establishment of a joint navigation company as another aspect of
bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The monthly bulletin issued by the custom house
of Abu Dhabi revealed the volume of non-petroleum foreign trade of
the Emirate of Abu Dhabi in April amounted to about 556 million
U.S. dollars, of which imports stood at 518 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin said Japan ranked the first among the
emirate's trading partners in the field of imports with 107
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the emirate's exports, Canada ranked first with
6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- A study worked out by the Saudi consultative services
on the sugar industry estimates that the sugar needs in Saudi
Arabia will rise to 742,000 tons in the year 2006.
</P>
<P>
Printed in Wednesday's local press, the study said that despite
the united sugar company production of 515,000 tons of refined
sugar, Saudi Arabia still imported up to 554,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- An agreement was signed here by Jordanian and Japanese
companies, whereby the latter would allocate 10 million dollars to
finance the former's emergency water program for this summer as
announced last April.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to purchase 20 water tanks and pumps, 30
pumping transformers and pipes, and water from private well owners
and to finance the drilling of twenty new wells, to help meet the
needs of citizens particularly in the capital governorate.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The net profit of Israel's five major banks for
the first quarter of 1999 reached 763 million shekels (about 186
million U.S. dollars), an increase of 18 percent over last year's
first quarter figure of 647 million shekels (about 158 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The growth was attributed to declining inflation, continued
appreciation of the shekels and the banks' efforts to upgrade
their efficiency in the period, according to economists.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's biggest telephone company Bezeq lost 29.2
million shekels (about 7.12 million dollars) in the first quarter,
after having allocated 275 million shekels (about 67 million
dollars) for a reorganization program in the year 2000, which
includes 500-600 layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Bezeq officials said the continuing freeze of the company's
privatization also harms its business management. They expressed
hope that the privatization process would resume soon, before full
competition in the domestic telecommunications market is permitted.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Syrian Oil Company has renewed an agreement with
an Egyptian oil prospection company for drilling 75 exploratory
wells, Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdi el-Banbi said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
El-Banbi told reporters that the biggest international tender
for developing oil fields in Syria has also been awarded to the
Egyptian oil company, Enpi.
</P>
<P>
The minister added three Egyptian private companies are working
in Syria's oil sector and 120 Syrian engineers and technicians
have completed training courses in Egypt in the oil industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
