<HEADLINE> China Moves to Further Boost B Share Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- New measures to make the issue of B
shares by Chinese enterprises easier, in a bid to further boost
the B share market, have been announced today.
</P>
<P>
A circular issued by the China Securities Regulatory Commission
(CSRC) said that besides state-owned enterprises, now collectively-
owned and other forms of enterprises can apply for the issue of B
shares.
</P>
<P>
The CSRC also canceled the pre-qualification system under which
enterprises have to be approved in batches on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, applications would be reviewed and
approved in separate cases.
</P>
<P>
Though there are no written regulations prohibiting non-state-
owned enterprises from issuing B shares, analysts here said such a
rule has been actually practiced. They said the new measures mark
a positive change in the government's policy.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the government has approved 107 B shares. But the
market has been in a sustained slump in recent years, causing
grave concern over its future among investors.
</P>
<P>
Senior CSRC sources have on different occasions expressed the
government's determination to revitalize the market.
</P>
<P>
The securities market watchdog last Friday announced the cut of
stamp tax over B share trading from 0.4 percent to 0.3 percent, as
from Monday, in its first attempt to save the market.
</P>
<P>
The B share market has recorded heavy gains in the last week,
mainly driven by bullish sentiments in the A share market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
