<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: PLA Air Force Rescues Sick French Tourist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GOLMUD (QINGHAI), June 2 (Xinhua) -- A special Chinese People's
Liberation Army (PLA) Air Force jet was scrambled this afternoon
to fly to the rescue of a French traveler who suddenly fell
seriously ill while touring the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau and brought
the elderly tourist back to Beijing for urgent treatment.
</P>
<P>
Jean Escalon, 63, from Grenoble in France, arrived in China on
May 24 in the company of his nephew and traveled to the city of
Golmud on May 31, which is 2,800 meters above sea level in
northwest China's Qinghai Province. The two had plans to bicycle
to Lhasa, the capital of southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, Escalon felt a sudden pain in his lower right
back and was immediately sent to a nearby hospital where he was
initially diagnosed as suffering from renal colic resulting from
kidney stones.
</P>
<P>
"The illness was caused by overwork, lack of oxygen and drinks
during his journey," explained Cui Guohua, the hospital head. "The
stones have existed in the patient's kidney for some time though
they have never caused renal colic before," he added.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the hospital's efforts, Escalon was still in acute
pain, so his nephew, Fedirec Cancel, called the Beijing Office of
the AEA (Asia Emergency Assistance) International PTE Ltd.,
appealing for help.
</P>
<P>
"Upon receiving the phone call, we asked China's PLA air force
to help and within half an hour they had agreed," said Cui Heping,
a senior consultant of the Singapore-based AEA.
</P>
<P>
"I never expected that you could have got here from Beijing
less than 36 hours since I made the rescue request," Cancel told a
Chinese doctor who came here with the special plane.
</P>
<P>
The plane, whose chief pilot Colonel Zhou Guoqing has nearly 5,
000 hours of flying experience, left the airport in the western
suburbs of Beijing at 09:10 today and arrived in Golmud at 12:15
after a flight of 2,000 km.
</P>
<P>
When the plane arrived, two AEA doctors rushed to the hospital
for a thorough medical check-up of the patient and make the
necessary preparations for the transfer.
</P>
<P>
After enduring serious pain and eating nothing for two days,
Escalon was pale and weak in the emergency room of the hospital,
and the pain had spread to his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
"If the illness worsens, the patient will suffer from infection
and kidney exhaustion. A transfer to a Beijing hospital where the
most modern facilities are available is the best option," decided
Yang Wen, an AEA doctor.
</P>
<P>
At 14:10 today, Escalon was carried on board the special plane
which left the plateau for Beijing 20 minutes later. Escalon will
be taken to the International Clinic attached to the AEA.
</P>
<P>
This is not the first time that China's Air Force has sent
special planes to pick up foreign nationals who become seriously
ill in remote places. The AEA Beijing Office says it organizes 100
first aid flights every year, with nearly 40 of them by the PLA's
air force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Borrowings of Philippine Firms Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Medium- and long-term loans from
offshore sources approved by the Central Bank of the Philippines
plunged 32 percent to 640.7 million U.S. dollars in the last
quarter of 1998 from 947.3 million U.S. dollars for the same
period in 1997, sources of the bank said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Loan exposure from banks and financial institutions accounted
for the bulk of credits, totaling 341.4 million U.S. dollars in
the fourth quarter of 1998, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Credits obtained from bilateral agencies aggregated 143.7
million U.S. dollars during the period, they said.
</P>
<P>
Borrowings of the communications sector constituted almost 61
percent of credits or 385 million U.S. dollars, an increase of
200.5 million U.S. dollars or 109 percent from 184.5 million U.S.
dollars for the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector obtained 201.8 million U.S. dollars,
constituting 31 percent of the total credits, the sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
