<HEADLINE> Philippines to Issue Privatization Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will issue
some 75 million U.S. dollars worth of privatization bonds before
the end of the year, the proceeds of which could be used to fund
the projected 875 million U.S. dollar deficit in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Sources of the Central Bank of the Philippines said on
Wednesday that the privatization certificates would give investors
the right to purchase shares in companies privatized after the
launch of the issue.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu was quoted as saying that
the privatization bonds also present an opportunity for smaller
investors to acquire government bonds.
</P>
<P>
If the government gets adequate funds from the bonds, it may no
longer have to borrow funds to finance the projected 875 million
U.S. dollar deficit next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bonds would have a maturity of five years, he added.
</P>
