<HEADLINE> Britain Says Ahtisaari Could Make Peace Mission to Belgrade Alone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said on Wednesday the European Union envoy to Yugoslavia, Finnish
President Martti Ahtisaari, could travel alone on a peace mission
to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
"Neither he nor we have excluded the possibility that at some
point it might be appropriate for him to go alone," Cook told
reporters at a daily briefing on the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Cook said the decision on whether to make the trip must be made
by Ahtisaari himself but that the Finnish president had Britain's
wholehearted support whatever he decided to do.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari previously planned to make a trip to Belgrade with
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin. But their departure was put
off while a new round of talks was held in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
An Itar-Tass report said earlier that the talks failed to reach
an agreement on a joint position regarding Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and
Ahtisaari have been in Bonn trying to agree on a position on
Kosovo since Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cook said Ahtisaari obviously felt he was close to agreement
with Chernomyrdin on a possible peace formula to take to Belgrade
together -- otherwise the two men would not have continued talks
on Wednesday in Bonn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
