<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Developing Third-Generation Mobile Telecom System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese version of the third-
generation of mobile telecommunications system, called IMT-2000,
is being developed by the China Research Institute of Mobile
Telecommunications Science and Technology with the approval of the
Ministry of Information Industry.
</P>
<P>
Headed by Yang Yigang, the research body's experts are seeking
ways to perfect their technological plans, while actively
participating in the international efforts to unify the different
standards of the systems.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that the global sales of mobile telephones
will reach 500 billion to one trillion U.S. dollars by 2010, and
most international telecom giants are sparing no effort in
developing their own systems, in order to secure bigger shares of
the market by incorporating more of their technical standards into
the global one in the making.
</P>
<P>
In June last year, China submitted a technical standard
proposal (TD-SCDMA) to the International Telecommunication Union (
ITU) in an attempt to gain a position in the future
standardization procedures related to IMT-2000.
</P>
<P>
Most of the international telecom giants have also reached a
consensus to support the proposal. Once taken, Chinese
manufacturing enterprises will have opportunities to enter the
world market.
</P>
<P>
China supports the convergence of different standards for third-
generation mobile phones and plans to commercialize the system
between the years 2002 and 2003, an Information Industry Ministry
official said.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to standardize technologies related with third-
generation mobile telecommunications system, the ITU started
evaluating various standards in 1985 and had received 15 different
proposals by last June.
</P>
<P>
China, with the world largest mobile phone market potential,
plays a key role in the standardization drive.
</P>
<P>
However, the ITU failed to reach a uniform set of standards
because of various interests represented by world telecom giants.
</P>
<P>
The typical candidate standards are the Wideband-Code Division
Multiple Access W-CDMA favored by European and Japanese companies,
and the CDMA2000 supported by North American companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0140 </DOCNO>
