<HEADLINE> EU Leaders To Focus On War in Balkans During Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the 15 European Union (
EU) member states will meet in Cologne, Germany, on Thursday and
Friday for a European Council that is expected to focus on the war
in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders will be discussing in depth the situation in the
Balkan nation. EU foreign ministers plan to debate a joint
strategy for a lasting peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss the results of a visit to Belgrade by the EU
envoy, Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who has been entrusted
with a mandate to go to Belgrade on behalf of the EU on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari met with Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, U.S.
Assistant Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, and German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder in Bonn on Tuesday to discuss aspects of his
Belgrade mission. He is expected to be accompanied by
Chernomyrdin on this peace mission.
</P>
<P>
EU sources said the Bonn meeting would ensure that conditions
set by NATO have indeed been met. According to the German
government, the Finnish president will not be going to Belgrade to
negotiate but to present Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
with a set of NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
The EU Summit will mark the end of Germany's six-month-long EU
presidency. Finland will take over the rotating presidency on
July 1. In a letter dated May 31 to EU leaders, Schroeder invited
his counterparts to "once again enhance the capacity of the
European Union, and the effectiveness and legitimacy of its joint
action to bring it even closer to the citizens."
</P>
<P>
"This is a "sine qua non" for the enlargement of the European
Union," Schroeder said in the letter. The crisis in the Balkans
merely served to underpin the need for joint action at the
forthcoming European Council in Cologne, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
