<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Exports Fall by 9 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Romania's exports fell by 9
percent in the first quarter of 1999, compared with the same
period of last year, the local Nine O'clock daily reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"This figure represents the most important fall of exports in
the past 10 years," the newspaper quoted Mihai Ionescu, executive
secretary of the National Association of Exporters and Importers
of Romania, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Trade deficit in the first three months was 418.1 million U.S.
dollars as against 435.1 million dollars in the same period of
last year, but this occurred against the background of a
considerable decrease of both exports and imports.
</P>
<P>
The drastic drop of exports, explained by the low
competitiveness of Romanian products and the loss of some
traditional markets, led to decreased imports, while 80 percent of
exports rely on imported raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Imports in the first quarter was 2,282.3 million dollars, a
drop of 8.1 percent from the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Committee for Statistics, the
newspaper said that the most significant decreases in exports this
year were chemicals, foodstuffs, drinks, tobacco, pig iron, iron
and steel, cars, tractors and other motor vehicles. Significant
import decreases were registered by fuel, mineral oils and organic
chemicals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
