<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Bans Congratulatory Messages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
ordered Tuesday an immediate stoppage of using public funds on
congratulatory messages, a Nigerian daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by Dr. Doyin Okupe, the
special assistant to the president on media and publicity,
Obasanjo said, "henceforth, chief executives of any organization
in the federal public service that approve such wasteful
expenditure should be ready to pay for it from their own pockets,"
This Day, a major Nigerian daily, reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is a widely used practice for high-ranking officials to
publish congratulatory messages or advertisement in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
But while expressing appreciation for the felicitations and
goodwill conveyed through such messages by individuals and
corporate bodies to his administration, Okupe said the president
"believes as a matter of personal principle and style that such
practice is not only wasteful, but also borders on sycophancy."
</P>
<P>
The newly sworn-in president pledged in his inauguration speech
on May 29 that he will have anti corruption as a main focus for
his administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
