<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Beefs Up Force in S. State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The government has urgently deployed
150 more soldiers to the troubled Warri area in Nigeria's southern
oil rich Delta State as conflict there had taken a death toll of
more than 200.
</P>
<P>
Delta State Governor James Ibori also held an urgent meeting
Tuesday with leaders of Ijaw, Itsekiri, and Urhobo, the three main
ethnic groups in Warri region.
</P>
<P>
Four soldiers were feared dead apart from the about 200
civilian death toll.
</P>
<P>
Militant Ijaw youths Monday torched the entire Itsekiri
dominant village of Aroton, including two primary and one
secondary schools, reported The Guardian, a major Nigerian paper,
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The youth started their assault early Monday morning after
disarming security personnel in a nearby camp. Aroton village was
located in Warri southwest local government area of Delta State.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere in the oil rich region was extremely tense when
Itsekiri youths are expected to fight back in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Although Delta governor pledged his support for the agitation
by the youths for better stake in the national resources located
in their communities, he condemned the use of violence.
</P>
<P>
The trouble was triggered when tax collectors from the two
council areas, which are in a hot debate over the ownership of the
area, are on their revenue drives one week ago.
</P>
<P>
Warri area is traditionally a headache for the state as well as
federal government, for the local ethnic communities are
constantly fighting against each other and the government on
division of land and oil benefit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
