<HEADLINE> S. Korean Club Storms to Winning Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, Anhui, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Samsung Fire &AMP; Marine
Insurance club spiked their way to a winning start in the opener
of the first AVC Cup Men's Club Tournament campaign here on
Wednesday by thrashing Paykan club of Iran.
</P>
<P>
The club, with five internationals in the line-up, showed their
advantages in experience and fine balance in both attack and
defence in a 25-20, 17-25, 25-20 thriller which adopted a rally
point scoring system.
</P>
<P>
Samsung showed their teeth from the outset and overcame the
charge of the Iranian team who rebounded to 7-7, 14-14 in the
thick of the first set.
</P>
<P>
The Korean side allowed few chances for Paykan in the second
set and maintained their lead all the way as they impressed the
capacity crowd with their relentless spikes and solid defence.
</P>
<P>
Paykan had to burn their bridge under the best-of-five format
as they stole a temporary lead in the third set but Samsung fought
back with their powerful spikes to pull the game 7-all and
retained their winning momentum before they sealed the match.
</P>
<P>
Paykan head coach Mehranpoor Hossein Ali said at the postmatch
press conference that they were defeated by the jinks on their
meeting against South Korea.
</P>
<P>
"We had lost to the name of the South Korea rather than to
their players," said the coach.
</P>
<P>
But they later corrected themselves saying that their problems
lay with their shortage of international experiences.
</P>
<P>
"We have few international experiences for we have only two
major international matches every year. we play about ten matches
home and abroad in total."
</P>
<P>
Samsung head coach Shin Chi-Yong did not stay long over the
opening success while he put his eyesight on the showdown with
Sichuan Fu Lan of China and NEC Blue Rockets of Japan.
</P>
<P>
"I think we did a better job in the preparation for the opener
than Iran. In this tournament we regarded the Chinese and Japanese
as the main threat."
</P>
<P>
The AVC Cup Men's Club Tournament, which was launched after the
Asian Club Championships had its ten-version spell ended, has
pitched the league champions of the Asian countries including
China, Japan, South Korea, Qatar and Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
