<HEADLINE> Chinese, Russian FMs Issue Joint Press Communique (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
6. China and Russia express their deep worry at the serious
complication in international situation caused by NATO's
bombardment of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agree that the act is a serious violation of the
U.N. Charter and acknowledged norms of international laws. NATO's
immediate halting of military operations is a necessary condition
to resolve the Kosovo issue by political means.
</P>
<P>
The two sides advocate that the United Nations should play its
due role in tackling the crisis. And any solution should deed the
opinions of Yugoslavia, one of the main parties involved.
</P>
<P>
The move that the chief prosecutor of the criminal tribunal of
the former Yugoslavia signed an indictment of the supreme
political and military leaders of Yugoslavia cannot be considered
an non-political act, which can only further complicate the
negotiation process.
</P>
<P>
Both agreed that continued aggression against Yugoslavia will
further worsen the Balkan situation and have an adverse impact on
the peace and stability in Europe, and even other parts of the
world.
</P>
<P>
The Russian side again condemns NATO's attack on the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade. Russia considers the move a gross
encroachment of Chinese sovereignty and the norms of international
laws. Russia supports China's just and fully grounded stance on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia are willing to continue their efforts in
seeking a political solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
