<HEADLINE> Greek Premier Expects War in Yugoslavia to End Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
said Tuesday that the war in Yugoslavia might end soon.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local television, Simitis said that the
Yugoslav war waged by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
was very likely to end by June 13 when the European Parliament
elections take place, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA)
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The premier voiced his dissatisfaction with Europe, saying that
Europe could have been the "other pole" of power in the world, but
showed weakness while the U.S. took advantage of the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
During celebrations for NATO's 50th anniversary in Washington
in late April, Simitis revealed, the large majority of
participating leaders rejected the idea by U.S. President Bill
Clinton of a possible change of borders in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the idea was not accepted by NATO, but it was
telling the way of the U.S. regards the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the Kosovo crisis, Greece, a member of NATO
and the European Union (EU), has insisted that it favors a
peaceful solution to the crisis instead of a NATO military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
Greece also warns that the change of borders in the Balkans can
lead to a widespread war in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
