<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Wednesday termed as "realistic" the latest remarks made
by Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz on relations with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Abdullah's remarks was an indication of the
"positive atmosphere, spirit of realism and transparency
prevailing in the bilateral relations," the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Asharq al-Awsat daily published on
Tuesday, Saudi Prince Abdullah said promotion of the ties between
his country and Iran would benefit the whole region.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi prince also defended Iran's right to boost its
defense.
</P>
<P>
"Iran has every right to develop its defense capabilities for
its security without harming others," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Iran and Saudi Arabia, as two powerful regional
states, would certainly play important roles in establishing and
strengthening peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations based on the principle of transparency
are expanding, concern about each other has been wiped out and
mutual trust and cooperation are developing, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Arab states have been wary of Iran's military
development since the 1979 Islamic revolution. But ties between
the two sides have improved since Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami came to power in 1997, particularly following his
ground-breaking visit to Saudi Arabia in May. 
</P>
