<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Keppel TatLee Bank to Give up 24.9 Pct Equity Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Keppel TatLee Bank Limited, one
of the largest banks in Singapore, Wednesday signed an
in-principle agreement with the Allied Irish Banks (AIB) to
relinquish its 24.9 percent equity stake to AIB.
</P>
<P>
A joint press release said this strategic alliance provides for
the two banks to work closely together to significantly enhance
Keppel TatLee Bank's activities in Singapore and the region, and
reposition the bank in the context of the deregulation of the
Singapore Banking Market.
</P>
<P>
It also said AIB will be issued bonds totaling approximately
350 million Singapore dollars (about 203.49 million U.S. dollars)
at one percent coupon rate with 350 million warrants which can be
exercised over a period of three years into 350 million Keppel
TatLee Bank shares at 4.18 Singapore dollars (about 2.43 U.S.
dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
The warrants will bring AIB' total investment to 1.5 billion
Singapore dollars (about 872 million U.S. dollars) and the move
will make shareholders' fund of Keppel TatLee exceeding 5 billion
Singapore dollars (about 2.91 billion U.S. dollars) within three
years.
</P>
<P>
Keppel Corporation Limited, which currently has 36 percent
equity in the Keppel TatLee Bank, will continue to hold about 30
percent interest in the enlarged Keppel TatLee Bank.
</P>
<P>
AIB's acquisition of a quarter of Keppel TatLee Bank's equity
stake came two weeks after the Monetary Authority of Singapore
announced measures to liberalize commercial banking and upgrade
local banks.
</P>
<P>
In the announcement, the Singapore government lifted the 40
percent foreign shareholding limit of local banks.
</P>
<P>
Keppel TatLee, merged by Keppel Bank and TatLee Bank last year,
presently has 59 branches and 110 ATMs in Singapore and three
branches and six representative offices abroad.
</P>
<P>
AIB Group, having a market capitalization of 25 billion
Singapore dollars (about 14.53 billion U.S. dollars) and enjoying
a pre-tax profit of 1.9 billion Singapore dollars (about 1.10
billion U.S. dollars) for 1998, operates principally in Ireland,
Britain, the U.S. and also in Central Europe and Asia. It employs
24,000 people worldwide in more than 900 branches and has 66,000
shareholders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
