<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary Reiterates Key NATO Objectives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said Wednesday that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic "must
accept the key NATO objectives of taking Serb forces out of Kosovo
and letting NATO forces in."
</P>
<P>
Cook's comments came as Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin prepared for a joint Russian-EU
peace mission to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
"Not because those are our demands but because those are the
minimum conditions for the refugees to return. That's got to be
the key outcome if we're going to secure peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cook said it was unclear whether Milosevic was willing to sign
up to those principles, but if he did there was a good chance of
success for the peace mission.
</P>
<P>
"If he is now willing to accept that, then there is a good
prospect of being able to close a deal," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, an adviser to the Foreign Ministry in
Belgrade, Miraslav Paic, told BBC radio that Yugoslavia was quite
willing to negotiate "but we are not going to accept any kind of
dictate."
</P>
<P>
The makeup of the peacekeeping force should be subject to
discussion between Yugoslav and United Nations authorities, but
Yugoslavia could not accept forces from countries that had been
involved in the Kosovo conflict, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for Yugoslav troop withdrawals, Paic said Yugoslavia had the
right to defend its borders, but "this question can be resolved
and addressed during the negotiations. We are ready to scale down
our presence to peacetime presence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
