<HEADLINE> British Part-Time Troops Refuse Balkan Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain's part-time soldiers are
refusing to volunteer for duty in the Balkans because they say the
government is trying to get their services on the cheap, the Daily
Mail reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, quoting unidentified officers from the volunteer
Territorial Army, said the soldiers were concerned about
ministers' refusal to guarantee their jobs and pensions while
serving with the regular British army in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
"The resulting lack of volunteers from the Territorial Army
could undermine (Prime Minister) Tony Blair's plans to send a 19,
000 strong force to the war zone in the next few weeks, to be
ready if NATO decides to send in ground troops," the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Officers said that their infantry units had been called upon to
provide scores of extra men to reinforce regular battalions which
had already been placed on standby for the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"We have been asked to supply 100 soldiers for the regular
battalion as volunteers," said an officer from one Territorial
Army unit.
</P>
<P>
"At the end of the day, we have families, mortgages and jobs,
and the government won't guarantee them, so we have refused," the
officer was quoted saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
