<HEADLINE> Two Killed Hours Before Polls Open in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A woman in KwaZulu-Natal's
Richmond hot spot and a policeman in Gauteng were shot dead in
separate attacks just hours before polls opened for the country's
national elections Wednesday, South African Press Association
(SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Both attacks occurred around midnight.
</P>
<P>
Four gunmen opened fire on a house in the African National
Congress- dominated Mozambique section of Ndaleni in Richmond
after ordering the occupants to push money underneath the door.
</P>
<P>
The woman, who had responded to their demand, was killed and a
man was wounded.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted Inspector Victor Hunt as saying that the suspects
allegedly fled toward Ezimozomeni -- believed to be the home of
United Democratic Movement supporters.
</P>
<P>
Police are investigating whether the attack was politically or
criminally motivated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Captain Oswald Meyer of the northern KwaZulu-Natal
security operations center said Wednesday morning that the
flash-point areas -- including Nongoma -- had been peaceful
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Gauteng policeman was ambushed by a group of men as he left
a house near Daveyton.
</P>
<P>
Despite the incidents, the general election is running smoothly
across the country, although the process was slow in some areas.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 police officers and soldiers have been deployed
around the country to ensure a peaceful ballot for the 18,3
million registered voters.
</P>
<P>
The 14,695 voting stations around the country open at 7 a.m.
(0500 GMT). 
</P>
</TEXT>
