<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila Wants to Get More Money from Japan, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
Kicked off Wednesday morning his eight-day visit to Japan and
South Korea with the aim to attract more foreign investments and
strengthen bilateral relations with its two long-time trading
partners.
</P>
<P>
During his June 2-5 working visit to Japan and June 6-9 state
visit to Republic of Korea, the president will do his best to get
more economic benefits for the Philippines. some 130 business
leaders will accompany the president on the tour.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, the president will have an audience with Japanese
Emperor Akihito and meet with Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Japan has committed over 3 billion U.S. dollars of the
record-high 4.5 billion U.S. dollar pledge garnered by the
Philippines during the recent Consultative Group Meeting in Tokyo
among foreign-aid donors.
</P>
<P>
It has also committed 500 million Japanese yen (4.17 million
U.S. dollars) for Mindanao's food security program, as well as 1
billion U.S. dollars of the Obuchi fund and about 6 billion U.S.
dollars of the Miyazawa aid initiative to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, Estrada will convey the Philippines'
appreciation to Seoul for the grant of financial assistance for
the establishment of the Korea-Philippines Friendship Hospital.
</P>
<P>
As Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said on Tuesday,
Estrada will take the opportunity to project a positive image of
the Philippines by highlighting the strengths of the country's
economy as well as its ability to cope with the regional currency
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The trip will likewise promote stronger cooperation between the
private sectors of the countries involved and pave the way for the
exploration of business possibilities and opportunities, leading
to the forging of business partnerships for mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, the president is expected to sign three project
agreements amounting to 3 billion Japanese yen (25 million U.S.
dollars), which covers food, education and financial area.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine President will also seek the support of the
Japanese government regarding Manila's request for the restoration
of the lost slots of Philippine Airlines at Narita during the
Winter and Summer schedules and the provision of additional time
slots and extra flights.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Estrada will discuss important bilateral issues
and concerns with the Japanese hosts, including the implementation
of Japan's financial assistance measures in the Philippines,
particularly those funded through the New Miyazawa Initiative.
</P>
<P>
In Seoul, Estrada will have a meeting with Korean President Kim
Dae Jung to discuss reform measures undertaken by their respective
governments to address the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine President will request his South Korea
counterpart to further reduce the tariff rate on Philippine
bananas and facilitate the exports of fresh Philippine coconut
water to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Both sides will also sign an agreement on a Korea-Philippines
Friendship Hospital, which involves the upgrading of the Andres
Bonifacio Memorial Hospital in Cavite in northern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Strengthening cooperation in Asia is another key issue on
Estrada's visiting agenda.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Japanese leaders, the Philippine
president will convey the Philippine government's views on the
framework for future cooperation in Asia, and to relay the
Philippine government's commitment to development and cooperation
as a means towards international stability and development.
</P>
<P>
When he meets Korean President Kim Dae Jung, Estrada is
expected to express the Philippines' support for the South Korea's
sunshine policy and other peace initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of Estrada and Kim will highlight the 50
anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations between
the Philippines and South Korea, which is being commemorated this
year.
</P>
<P>
He will discuss with Kim the third Asia-Europe Meeting in the
year 2000 in Seoul, cooperation in the United Nations, and the
establishment of the East Asian Vision Group, a proposal made by
President Kim during last year's leaders' meeting of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Vision Group will be composed of eminent
intellectuals charged with the task of drawing up a vision for
mid-to-long term cooperation in East Asia for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Estrada is likewise expected to extend an invitation to Kim to
attend the ASEAN +3 and ASEAN +1 Summit in Manila this November.
</P>
<P>
Since Japan and South Korea are hosts to a big number of
Filipinos, the two-nation swing will also enable the Philippine
president to interact with leaders and representatives of Filipino
communities there.
</P>
<P>
For 1998, the Philippine Embassy in Tokyo reported that there
is a total of 245,518 Filipinos in Japan.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the total estimated member of Filipinos in
South Korea as of March 1999 is placed at 15,000. Of the total,
7,600 are documented while 6,900 are considered illegal workers.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has made it a point to meet with overseas Filipino
workers, whom he has hailed as the country's "modern-day heroes."
 
</P>
</TEXT>
