<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Falae Greets President Obasanjo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In an advertisement, Falae who lost the February 27
presidential election said, "I wish to congratulate General
Olusegun Obasanjo and Alhaji Abubakar Atiku on the occasion of
their swearing-in and installation as the president and
vice-president of the Federal Republic of Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
Falae's congratulatory message came as a surprise to many
Nigerians as the APP candidate had refused to acknowledge
Obasanjo's victory in the February 27 polls which he stated was
marred by irregularities allegedly perpetrated by Obasanjo's party
of the People's Democratic Party (PDP).
</P>
<P>
Falae, the joint presidential candidate of APP and the Alliance
for Democracy (AD) who polled over 11 million votes compared with
Obasanjo's more than 18 million vowed to challenge Obasanjo's
victory at the election petition tribunals.
</P>
<P>
He rejected appeals from some quarters of the country that he
should not file a petition against Obsanjo's victory to avoid a
situation where some adventurous military officers would utilize
the opportunity to derail the transition program, and filed a
petition at the Federal Court of Appeal against Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
The Court of Appeal, however, dismissed all the charges raised
by Falae and declared Obasanjo validly elected as the president of
the Fourth Republic of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Following the court dismissal, Falae refused to explore the
last legal option of filing an appeal at the Supreme Court, saying
that "while there is great public sympathy and support for our
cause, there is widespread concern that a protracted legal battle
may be used as an excuse by ambitious military elements to prolong
military rule in the country." 
</P>
</TEXT>
