<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke060237-Vietnamese Businesses Urged to Be Ready for Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese businesses have not paid
sufficient attention to the country's process of integrating into
the regional and world economy, Vietnam's Deputy Minister of Trade
Tran Duc Minh said.
</P>
<P>
Minh said at a seminar Tuesday on regional and global
integration  that "Vietnamese firms have not actually outlined
business plans to help them survive the harsh competition when
Vietnam phases out its non-tariff barriers with regional
countries."
</P>
<P>
The seminar was attended by executives of foreign-invested
companies in Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
A majority of enterprises, Minh said, were still holding the
false idea that they could rely on the government protectionist
measures.
</P>
<P>
Certain sensitive items like steel, vehicles, sugar, seafood,
rice and coffee are now still protected by the Vietnamese
government.
</P>
<P>
However, Minh warned that the current protectionism could not
last long. Therefore, he said, Vietnamese enterprises have to
restructure their production and enhance management.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is trying to gradually integrate with the regional and
world economy and became a member of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations in July 1995 and a member of the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation in November 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
