<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: CDMA Forerunners Eye Asia Market (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hinton said that China is the world's largest potential market
for whatever technologies which are new, whether it is of
refrigerators, computers or wireless devices. And China is leading
the CDMA industry as represented by the trial of new networks in
several big cities.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is actually the birth place of CDMA in Asia and the
success of Hutchison's CDMA network in Hong Kong is well known,
Hinton said.
</P>
<P>
According to Hinton, Motorola, providing CDMA systems in eight
countries and areas in Asia, is also a supplier of one of the
initial CDMA networks in China. Motorola provides networks in
Beijing and the number of subscribers based there is now
approaching 14,000 on that very small system.
</P>
<P>
Motorola has established the first CDMA manufacturing joint
venture in East China's Hangzhou in 1996 and this joint venture
provides a big portion of Beijing operational networks.
</P>
<P>
David Ho, senior vice president of wireless networks for
Greater China of Nortel Networks, said that every CDMA supplier is
interested in China, "the biggest untapped market."
</P>
<P>
Nortel has a CDMA system in Northwest China's Xi'an and has
recently established a joint venture in China.
</P>
<P>
Paul Calcott, marketing and strategy director of Asia Pacific
Wireless Networks of Lucent Technologies, said the Asia pacific is
"quite unique" in a lot of ways because Asian countries do not
develop at the same rate.
</P>
<P>
"A change we have seen in the industry is that the products in
the communications mechanism is much more lifestyle driven rather
than technology driven," said Calcott.
</P>
<P>
"One of the objectives for us in the industry should be that
wireless and CDMA technology become the preferred access for
consumers," Calcott said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, "what we are hoping to come out of the (
CDMA) world congress is certainly some real driving points that
take us to the next step we need to take," particularly for a
region like the Asia Pacific where the CDMA industry grows at a "
phenomenal rate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lucent Technologies, in the forefront of implementing wireless
systems worldwide, now has CDMA networks in five countries.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of CDMA in China represents nothing more than
the introduction of extension of competition, Hinton said.
</P>
<P>
"I really believe this is much more positive for the overall
market than the negative," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ho said that he believes the deployment of CDMA in China will
just "make the pie bigger, but not smaller," adding that China
Telecom will continue to grow GSM, PCS200 and it will continue to
be a market leader as far as the subscribers are concerned.
</P>
<P>
All these executives have expressed their support to Hong
Kong's ambitious plan to develop into a information technology hub
in the region, in particular, the multi-billion-dollar Cyberport
project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
