<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Standardize Market Activities of Private Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China has boosted it efforts to
standardize and control the activities of private businesses,
which have been given more development room than years ago, in a
bid to keep the market in good order.
</P>
<P>
All levels of administrations for industry and commerce in
China handled 137,700 cases of irregular activities involving
private firms in the first quarter of this year involving fines
totaling 37.51 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, more than 4,000 private firms were
ordered to suspend business for regulation violations and another
6,600 illegally established firms had their business licenses
revoked.
</P>
<P>
The cases fell into six categories: a total of 85,700 cases
violated registration regulations; more than 15,000 cases involved
infringements of consumer rights; 1,100 cases violated the Unfair
Competition Law; the other three categories involved scalping
prohibited goods, selling fake or shoddy products, and producing
illegal publications.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration for Industry and Commerce is urging
relevant departments to enhance market supervision by combating
forgery of brandname products, closing down illegally set up firms
and other monitoring efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Slightly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
marginally lower Wednesday, with the market brushing aside robust
growth figures in favor of a poor commodity prices outlook.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended in Sydney at 64.48 U.S. cents, from
64.60 U.S. cents Tuesday, having traded between 64.20 and 64.60
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Australia's gross domestic product (GDP) grew by 1.1 percent,
seasonally adjusted, in the quarter ending in March for an annual
growth of 4.8 percent, the Australian Bureau of Statistics said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite being slightly above expectations, the data was
overshadowed by pessimism over longer term factors such as the
continuing poor outlook on commodity prices, a new 20-year low in
the price of gold, and the impact of a rate hike in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also closed locally at 0.6167 euro from
0.6190 euro Tuesday and 77.67 Japanese yen from 78.24 yen.
</P>
</TEXT>
