<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Traditional Chinese Medicine Guide to Be Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An up-to-date guide to the use of
traditional Chinese medicine is to be published later this year
which experts believe will become the definitive work on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
The 30-volume "Materia Medica of China" will contain
information on nearly 9,000 kinds of herbal medicines and drugs
made from animal materials or minerals, according to the State
Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine, which initiated
the work in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Each entry will have a description of its outward appearance,
chemical composition and functions, the planting and processing
methods, as well as clinical research results.
</P>
<P>
The books will also include details of some 1,500 kinds of
medicines that are used by some of China's ethnic groups, such as
the Tibetan, Mongolian, Uygur and Dai peoples.
</P>
<P>
"These books are important traditional Chinese medicine
reference materials and incorporate the results of centuries of
experience in the field as well as the results of modern research,
" said Li Zhenji, deputy director of the Administration.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the "Compendium of Materia Medica", which was
compiled by Li Shizhen, a noted traditional Chinese medicine
master of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), is still regarded as the
leading guide to the use of traditional Chinese medicines. However,
it only contains information on 1,892 kinds of medicines.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 experts from some 60 domestic academies and
research institutes were involved in compiling the information
over the ten-year period, using over 10,000 kinds of ancient and
modern publications as references, according to the Shanghai
Science and Technology Publishing House, the publisher of the
pharmacopoeia which will hit the bookstores in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
