<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Keen to Work with Russia for Multi-Polar World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan said here today that China is keen to promote consultation
with Russia to establish a just and reasonable new international
order and a multi-polar world.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during talks with his Russian counterpart
Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that China and Russia share wide-ranging consensus on
the Kosovo issue, and have reached mutual understanding on related
issues. "China appreciates Russia's efforts to seek a political
solution of the Kosovo crisis," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov briefed Tang on Russia's view on the current
international situation, especially the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S.-led NATO should immediately stop bombing
to create conditions for restoring stability in Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that bilateral relations have maintained their good
development trend, especially after President Jiang Zemin visited
Russia last November, during which the two countries' heads of
state held their first unofficial meeting. And Premier Zhu Rongji
visited Russia last February, during which the two sides reached
consensus on expanding cooperation in all areas.
</P>
<P>
"Experience shows that establishing Sino-Russian strategic and
cooperative partnership is in the fundamental interests of the two
peoples," he said. He added that the two countries should make
full preparations for the second unofficial meeting between the
two heads of state to be held this fall, and take further measures
to implement all agreements signed in the fourth regular meeting
between the prime ministers of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that the two countries are good neighbors, and that
bilateral relations have developed remarkably in recent years. "
Russia and China, as two permanent members of the United Nations
Security Council, have promoted consultations and cooperation on
the international issues and Russia is satisfied with that," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two heads of state have defined the direction
and laid firm foundations for the development of Sino-Russian
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Economy Surges 4.8 Percent in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Australia's economic growth surged
beyond expectations in the first quarter of 1999 to 4.8 percent,
driven by booming consumer spending and a rebound in business
spending in preparation for computer year 2000 (Y2K) problems.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said Wednesday the
country's gross domestic product (GDP) grew 1.1 percent in the
March quarter, seasonally adjusted, bringing the annual growth to
4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The result was driven by booming household spending and boosted
business investment, with the main drags on growth being
languishing exports and a fall in government consumption, the ABS
said.
</P>
<P>
Australian Treasurer Peter Costello said the Australian economy
had put in a first-class performance of strong growth and low
inflation.
</P>
<P>
But the treasurer warned that while GDP growth may exceed the
government's forecast of 4.25 percent for the fiscal year of
1998-1999 ending on June 30, 1999, it may have peaked.
</P>
<P>
"Will the Australian economy keep up the clip of 4.8 percent in
(the fiscal year of) 1999/2000?" he asked. "We don't think so."
</P>
<P>
According to an ABS survey, a 21.6-percent rise in spending on
new machinery and equipment by the private sector - in preparation
for the Y2K computer bug - buoyed the growth.
</P>
<P>
Household final consumption expenditure rose by 1.7 percent,
while imports of goods and services increased by 3.9 percent as
exports fell slightly.
</P>
<P>
General government spending was down 3.2 percent but business
investment rebounded by 9.6 percent - even though it remained 7
percent lower than a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Strong growth in most retail sectors was offset by falls in
motor vehicle purchases and spending on cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
The Australian economy, the 14th largest in the world, grew by
4.7 percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
