<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Japanese Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing
said here today that Japan should stick to the road of peace and
development by using history as mirror and overcoming interference.
</P>
<P>
He told a delegation from Japan's Association of Governors
headed by its President Tsuchiya Yoshihiko that China and Japan
should further their cooperation as the 21st century approaches.
</P>
<P>
"Increasing ties between China and Japan would benefit peace
and stability in Asia and the rest of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed his hope that local governments of the two
countries should cement their cooperation and further exchanges
between the younger generation as an effort to push forward the
healthy advancement of bilateral friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
Tsuchiya said that his delegation was very glad to have the
opportunity to visit China while the country is preparing to
celebrate the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
He added that during Chinese President Jiang Zemin's Japan
visit last year, the two countries released a joint declaration
for furthering the bilateral relations geared towards the 21st
century, and that Japan should make efforts to implement the
declaration.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that tragies in history should not be repeated and
that Japan should make serious reparations for the past in order
to make contributions to peace in Asia and the rest of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
