<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympics Reinstate Cycling Road Race Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The organisers of the 2000 Sydney
Olympic Games announced on Wednesday that they were reinstating
the cycling road race course.
</P>
<P>
The organising committee SOCOG said last month that it was
moving the race to another course west of Sydney to save money,
also to avoid a possible compensation claim from Rupert Murdoch's
Fox studios.
</P>
<P>
But the SOCOG was forced to change its mind under the pressure
of the International Cycling Union (UCI). The UCI complained that
the new course would not be testing enough for a top race and
Olympic road planners said it would disrupt traffic.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG vice-president John Coates said on Wednesday that SOCOG
had proposed reinstating most of the original course, including a
steep climb up from the Pacific ocean.
</P>
<P>
But the road races would now start and finish at the Sydney
Cricket Ground instead of the Sydney Football Stadium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
