<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthens External Audit of Foreign Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC),
the country's central bank, today issued guidelines for the
external auditing of overseas-funded banks, which is a necessary
part of the supervision of China's banking sector.
</P>
<P>
They set out the rules for overseas banks using registered
accountants as well as the required qualifications for accountancy
firms involved in external auditing for overseas banks.
</P>
<P>
Essentially the guidelines stipulate that overseas banks should
engage only one accountancy firm to audit all their activities in
China, and that those firms should have no fewer than 20
registered accountants with some obviously familiar with
international banking business.
</P>
<P>
Registered accountants are required, in line with the
guidelines, to audit the closing fiscal year accounts of overseas
banks, as well as assessing their assets, liabilities, profits and
losses, asset quality, financial reports filed to the PBOC,
internal control systems, computer systems and information
management systems.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines also explain the procedures for the appointment
of registered accountants by overseas banks, the auditing methods,
the training of registered accountants, auditing reports and other
aspects of the work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Former President Files Suit Against Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former president
Soeharto Wednesday filed a defamation suit against the U.S. news
magazine Time for a report alleging that he and his family have
amassed a 15 billion U.S. dollar fortune.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto went to the national police headquarters, accompanied
by his eldest daughter Siti Hardiyanti "Tutut" Rukmana, and six of
his eight lawyers, to file the suit.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who will be 78 next Tuesday, reiterated that the
leading American magazine's report on his wealth is a lie and
constitutes defamation.
</P>
<P>
Time reported that the Soehartos' fortune includes 9 billion
U.S. dollars in cash that was transferred from a bank in
Switzerland to another bank in Austria shortly after the former
ruler was forced from office in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto asserted in a recent private television interview that
he did not own a single cent in foreign banks and he challenged
the government and the general public to trade whatever wealth he
possesses overseas.
</P>
<P>
As Soeharto filed a defamation suit against Time at police
headquarters, his youngest son Hutomo Mandala Putra, alias Tommy,
was summoned by the Attorney General here Wednesday in connection
with the magazine's report.
</P>
<P>
According to the Attorney General Office's spokesman
Soehandoyo, the prosecution team members raised eight questions
with Tommy in connection with his wealth, as reported in the
magazine's May 24 edition.
</P>
<P>
He said Tommy answered most of the questions in a hand-written
format.
</P>
<P>
Besides Tommy, his brothers Sigit Harjojudanto (Soeharto's
eldest son) and Bambang Trihatmodjo (Soeharto's second son), and
his sister Tutut had previously been summoned in connection with
the same case.
</P>
<P>
According to a tentative schedule, Soeharto's daughters Siti
Hediyati "Titiek" Harjadi and Siti Hutami "Mamiek" Endang
Adiningsih will be questioned on Thursday and Friday respectively.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
