<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dollar Plunges Steeply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar has kept
sliding in its value and is now down more than 6 percent compared
with levels less than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The NZ dollar was down more than half a cent of the U.S. dollar
 Wednesday to less than 53 cents of the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
It has also weakened against the Australian currency from 84.5
cents of an Australian dollar at the start of May to 81.6 cents
Wednesday, the lowest rate since 1994.
</P>
<P>
A fortnight ago, Governor Don Brash of the Reserve Bank (New
Zealand's central bank) warned local financial markets that he was
 puzzled by the rising value of the New Zealand dollar. The
currency had risen on the expectation of stronger commodity
prices around the world, improved world economic growth and a
greater demand for the New Zealand currency to buy shares in
Contact Energy which the New Zealand government sold recently.
</P>
<P>
Local economists hold that the New Zealand dollar tends to move
in tandem with the Australian currency as both are linked to the
state of international commodity prices. They said the rapidly
falling New Zealand dollar helps the exports of the country.
</P>
<P>
Economists with the Bank of New Zealand have been encouraged to
lift the bank's forecast for New Zealand economic growth this year
from 2 percent to 3 percent, a Wellington-based newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion quoted the bank as saying that it has revised its
view because the New Zealand dollar is likely to remain at
competitive levels this year.
</P>
<P>
"Recent falls in the New Zealand dollar have pushed it to more
realistic levels," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petrol Prices in New Zealand Keep Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The household petrol price index
 in New Zealand fell for the fifth consecutive quarter, down 2.2
percent between the fourth quarter of last year and the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, the Statistics New Zealand said Wednesday
that the commercial price indexes for bulk petrol and diesel also
fell, down 0.8 and 0.7 percent respectively in the first quarter
this year.
</P>
<P>
Household consumers are paying 10.8 percent less for petrol
than they did in the fourth quarter of 1998, it said, adding the
main reasons for this appeared to be increased competition between
petrol retailers and low world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, electricity generation in the first
quarter was 1.6 percent lower than in the previous quarter. Hydro
generation decreased 12.8 percent due to South Island lakes
receiving their lowest inflows in more than 65 years. Thermal
generation increased by 31.2 percent to compensate for the
reduction in hydro electricity generation.
</P>
<P>
Gas production for the first quarter was 3.9 percent higher
than a year earlier. Increased gas use in the power generation and
methanol sectors are possible explanations for this rise, the
Statistics New Zealand said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Building Consents on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The total value of consents for
buildings issued in April by the concerned department of the New
Zealand government was 514.3 million New Zealand dollars (282
million U.S. dollars), one of the highest totals in the last 18
months, the Statistics New Zealand said in a media release
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Residential buildings had a big influence on the total, with
their total value reaching 349.3 million NZ dollars (192 million
U.S. dollars). A total of 2,253 consents worth 286.6 million NZ
dollars (157 million U.S. dollars) were issued for new dwellings
in April, the second highest monthly total since September 1997
and a 32 percent increase over the same month of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The rise was attributed to increased confidence in the economy
and low interest rates. It was the eighth consecutive month of
strong growth for the building of new dwellings, the Statistics
New Zealand said.
</P>
<P>
Non-residential buildings' value increased for the first time
since December 1997 to 165.1 million NZ dollars (90 million U.S.
dollars). The Statistics New Zealand cautioned that it was too
early to say if this marked a turning point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
