<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Seeks to Dispel Fears in Jezzine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's leading anti-Israeli
guerrilla group Hezbollah has renewed its assurances to Jezzine
residents in south Lebanon that it cared about their safety and
would not harm them after the pro-Israeli militia's departure.
</P>
<P>
"This is obvious from the sacrifices the resistance has made
throughout the years to liberate the area," Hezbollah's
secretary-general Sayyed Hassan Nasrallah told a delegation from
Jezzine Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Monday night, the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA) began
retreating from Jezzine, a Christian town it has held for 14
years, just north of the Israeli-occupied border zone in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The SLA decided to leave the area in the face of mounting
casualties from frequent roadside bombings launched by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah has been leading a war of attrition to oust Israeli
forces and the SLA out of Lebanon in 1985 when Israel set up a
self-declared security zone in the south of the country allegedly
to shield its northern area from attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The SLA's pullback has fueled fears among residents in Jezzine
that Hezbollah would enter the area and seek to revenge on
suspected collaborators with Israel or SLA.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah dismissed as "exaggerated" fears of Jezzine residents
that the town would be left in a dangerous security vacuum until
the deployment of Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that his fighters will not enter Jezzine and harass
its inhabitants and will not use it as a base for attacks against
Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
But, he stressed that those collaborators should be handed
over to the Lebanese judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong SLA, established in 1985, have been trained
and financed by Israel to help it patrol the occupied zone. Its
members are considered in Lebanon as traitors and its commander
Antoine Lahd has been sentenced to death in absentia by a Beirut
military court.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately clear whether the Lebanese army would
take over Jezzine after the SLA withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government has been reluctant to commit regular
troops to Jezzine lest it be interpreted as providing security
guarantees to Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss has assured local
residents in the town that the government would take full
responsibility for the security of the 5,000 population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
