<HEADLINE> Uganda, Congo (K) to Form Team to Implement Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Uganda and Congo
(K) have decided to form a committee of experts to facilitate
implementation of the Sirte Accord signed by Presidents Yoweri
Museveni and Laurent Kabila in Libya on April 18.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following talks between a Congolese
delegation and Museveni and senior Ugandan officials here over the
weekend, the New Vision newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The committee's mandate is to work out practical modalities for
the implementation of the accord, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The six-man Congolese delegation, spear-headed by Justice
Minister Mwenze Kongolo, arrived here last Friday night for
consultations with their Ugandan counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The Sirte Accord called for cessation of hostilities,
withdrawal of all foreign troops and deployment of neutral
peace-keeping forces in Congo (K) to supervise the withdrawal of
troops and to guarantee the security for neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese delegation left here for Lusaka, Zambia, Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
