<HEADLINE> Pacers Survive Drought, Battle to Win over Knicks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Facing an insumountable two-game
deficit in the NBA Eatern Conference finals, the Indiana Pacers
got a pair of free throws from Reggie Miller with two seconds left
to secure an 88-86 victory over the visiting New York Knicks
tonight.
</P>
<P>
Jalen Rose scored seven points in a 9-0 Indiana run in the
fourth quarter after the Knicks had rallied from a 55-38 deficit
to take a six-point lead.
</P>
<P>
The Pacers had missed 19 of 20 shots before the Rose-led spurt.
Knicks center Patrick Ewing missed a jumper at the buzzer that
would have sent the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
There were 68 fouls and 84 free throws. Miller, the league's
leading free throw shooter, calmly made both throws to give his
team the win in a game in which the Pacers blew a 17-point lead,
lost their starting center to fouls with more than six minutes
left.
</P>
<P>
The Pacers overcame an inspired performance from a Knicks team
that was undeterred by all the adversity that came its way.
</P>
