<HEADLINE> African States Urged to Improve Dissemination of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An official with the World Health
Organization (WHO) has urged African countries to improve their
capacity for collection, processing and dissemination of health
information.
</P>
<P>
The WHO country representative Edward Maganu said here Tuesday
while officially opening a four-day training course on the African
Index Medicus (AIM) that more often than not, African countries
depended on foreign data bases to have access to health
information, even on what is generated in their own land, Zambian
newspaper, the Post, reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"More of these data bases are expensive and do not carry a
comprehensive record of information generated in Africa," Maganu
said.
</P>
<P>
He commended University of Zambia for organizing the training
workshop whose aim was to improve Zambia's capacity for
collection, processing and dissemination of information.
</P>
<P>
Maganu assured Zambia of the world organization's continued
support through the provision of technical assistance to the AIM
project.
</P>
<P>
Lupambo Munkonge, dean of School of Medicine at the University
of Zambia, said poor communication among the participating
countries in AIM was affecting the indexing of African
publications on major international data bases.
</P>
<P>
"We in Zambia, through this training, try to overcome this
hurdle and take a lead in facilitating access to health
information so that we can share with other participating
countries," Munkonge said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
