<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislature to Evaluate Forest Law Enforcement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The National People's Congress (NPC)
, China's legislature, today exhibited its discontent with slow
growth of the country's forest coverage over the past two decades
in spite of increased funding and announced it will evaluate
implementation of the Forest Law.
</P>
<P>
"Afforestation efforts have been offset by massive illegal
logging and pilfering by both individuals and local state-owned
enterprises," said Buhe, vice chairman of the NPC Standing
Committee who will head fact-finding tours.
</P>
<P>
The current ratio of the nation's forest coverage is only 1.2
percent higher than in 1980, and currently stands at 13.92 percent,
or half the worldwide level.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the government has constantly augmented
allocations for planting and protecting trees, with last year's
inputs of 4.62 billion yuan representing a four-fold rise on 1997,
according to reports issued by the Finance Ministry and the State
Planning and Development Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government plans to allocate an additional 2.8
billion yuan this year to protect virgin forest in 12 provinces,
including Sichuan and Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Forestry points out that
destruction has accompanied the period of construction extending
over several years. The fact that many state-owned timber
enterprises controlled by local governments have ignored logging
quotas has greatly aggravated the situation already plagued by
theft and excessive logging on the part of individuals.
</P>
<P>
An additional 2.57 million hectares of forest land have been
illegally occupied for farm land or other uses since 1994,
according to the administration.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that related deforestation has further aggravated
damage created by natural disaster such as last year's record
summer flooding along the Yangtze River and in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
NPC fact-finding tours, which are scheduled to begin this month,
will mainly focus on the upper reaches of rivers in Heilongjiang
and Sichuan provinces and the Inner Mongolia and Guangxi Zhuang
autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Buhe instructs members of fact-finding missions to focus on
the responsibility local governments bear for enforcing the Forest
Law promulgated in 1985 and revised last year. The Forest Law was
designed as an effective tool to help attain the national goal of
increasing the forest coverage rate by 3.5 percent within 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela, Mbeki Cast Their Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Just after polling stations
opened for South Africa's second democratic election Wednesday
morning, its first citizen made his mark.
</P>
<P>
President Nelson Mandela, always an early riser, came to cast
his ballot at the Transvaal Automobile Club voting station north
of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Scores of local and international journalists crammed into the
tiny polling station to see Mandela place his vote in the ballot
box.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very wonderful occasion," said Mandela, who was
accompanied by his wife, Graca Machel. He said it was a great day
for South Africans to vote for a better life for all.
</P>
<P>
Asked who he was voting for, the president merely laughed.
</P>
<P>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki cast his vote in Hatfield,
Pretoria, saying that it was a proud day for all South Africans.
</P>
<P>
By voting, citizens were confirming their commitment to a
democratic society, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki is expected to be the next president.
</P>
<P>
He said the low levels of violence in the run up to the
election bode well for a free and fair outcome.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki denied there was a problem of voter apathy, pointing to
the queue outside the station, and said, "there is a lot of
enthusiasm."
</P>
<P>
Outside the polling station, some voters had been waiting since
the early hours of Wednesday to cast their ballot.
</P>
<P>
Deon Pieterse, 19, said he had been waiting since mid-night,
while some others reported waiting since 4:00 a.m. (0200 GMT).
</P>
<P>
"I want to be the first to vote," Pieterse said.
</P>
<P>
United Democratic Movement leader Bantu Holomisa also cast his
vote in Pretoria. He said he would later Wednesday visit polling
stations across the country.
</P>
<P>
New National Party leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk made his mark
in Western Cape, a province his party rules.
</P>
<P>
A smiling van Schalkwyk believed that the poll will be free and
fair. He said he is confident that his party will retain its
position as official opposition and will be able to continue to
rule in the Western Cape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
