<HEADLINE> Moi Presses for Special Courts for Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has asked the country's Chief Justice Zacchaeus Chesoni to set up
special courts to prosecute corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks Tuesday when he addressed the
nation in an off- the-cuff speech at Uhuru (freedom) Park in
Nairobi during the 36th Madaraka (internal self rule)
celebration, the East African Standard reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The special courts would be made up of a bench of judges, he
said, adding that many corruption cases were pending in the
courts, hence the need for the special courts to speed up the
hearing of those cases.
</P>
<P>
Moi decried the rampant corruption in the country, especially
in the civil service, saying the public sector was running down
the government's efforts at developing the nation.
</P>
<P>
He warned corrupt government employees that their time to face
the music had come and assured Kenyans that the Kenya
Anti-Corruption Authority will investigate and bring to justice
all corrupt individuals.
</P>
<P>
"Corruption must be eliminated if this country is to move into
the future with confidence and prosperity for all Kenyans," Moi
observed.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that civil servants were expected to maintain
integrity and high professional ethics in their work as
development projects implementers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
