<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Bank Share Capital Up: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has increased the share capital of its
bank to five billion U.S. dollars to widen the share-holding scale
by member states.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia newspaper Wednesday quoted Zambian Commerce,
Trade and Industry Minister David Mpamba as saying here that the
COMESA summit held in Kenya last month resolved to increase the
share capital to five billion dollars as equivalent of the COMESA
dollar.
</P>
<P>
He said all member states wishing to buy shares in the COMESA
bank should do so now as it would enhance the regional body's
trading capacity.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba said the meeting also resolved to prepare framework for
the creation of a single currency so that all member states use
one monetary unit by the year 2025.
</P>
<P>
The summit, at which Zambia handed over the chairmanship to
Kenya, also agreed to create the Africa Guarantee Fund (AGF) to
support countries that will be affected by the reduction of
tariffs in October 2000.
</P>
<P>
All COMESA countries are expected to zero rate their tariffs by
October 31 in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba said the council of ministers discussing the issue of
merging COMESA and the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) is resolved to refer the matter to the heads of state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
