<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Energy Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China is accelerating the
development of energy resources in a bid to basically meet the
demand for energy in the coming century and guarantee sustainable
economic development.
</P>
<P>
An official in charge of energy development in the State
Development Planning Commission said China will pay equal
attention to developing energy resources and saving energy in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
He noted that energy development in the next century will be
based on coal production and focused on power generation, and the
development of petroleum, natural gas, nuclear power, as well as
other new and renewable energy resources will be accelerated.
</P>
<P>
The official also noted that China will launch a series of
strategic drives in the next century. One of the drives, the coal
sector will be shifted westwards and great efforts will be made to
develop the Shenfu and Dongsheng coalfields and ease bottlenecks
in coal transportation.
</P>
<P>
In the power sector, China will accelerate construction of
hydroelectric power stations along major rivers and coal firing
power plants near coal mines.
</P>
<P>
The petroleum industry will prioritize oil and gas exploitation
in western China and in offshore areas.
</P>
<P>
In early next century, China's major coal bases will be in
Shanxi, Shaanxi, Heilongjiang and Guizhou provinces and western
Inner Mongolia, its major water-power producers will be on the
upper reaches of the Yellow River and the middle and lower reaches
of the Yangtze River, and its major oil supplier will be in Daqing
in the northeast and Shengli in the north.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Energy Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experts note that China will achieve balanced supply and demand
for energy by early next century.
</P>
<P>
They point out that the current net export volume of 30 million
tons of coal will be increased in the 21st century. However, no
big increases are expected for imported oil.
</P>
<P>
Estimates indicate the total consumption of the country's
nonrenewable energy resources will equal 1.38 billion tons of
standard coal in early next century, with coal output rising to 1.
45 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
China's annual oil production will hit 150 million tons and
gas production will stand at 25 billion cubic meters. In addition,
the country's major power grids will be linked nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Experts express confidence that the country's energy production
and reserves will effectively guarantee social and economic
developments in the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
