<HEADLINE> Diabetes Becomes Major Health Challenge in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Diabetes has emerged as one of
the major public health challenges in the Gulf countries as its
occurrence is rapidly rising.
</P>
<P>
Medicines for treatment of diabetes worth 10 million
U.S. dollars are sold annually in the six Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) countries, Dubai-based Khaleej Times reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain and the
United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
"The market for diabetes medicines, including injectables, has
been growing due to high percentage of population suffering from
it," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Studies have shown that nearly 10 percent of the world
population, about 100 million, are suffering from diabetes.
</P>
<P>
The prevalence rates are high in the Gulf region - 13 percent
in Saudi Arabia, 10 percent in Bahrain and 12 percent in Oman.
</P>
<P>
The overall prevalence rate of the disease in the Gulf is
between 4 to 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figure is doubled among those who are above 50 years of
age, with a preponderance for males and urban residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
