<HEADLINE> Malaysian Foreign Minister Cites Successful Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua)-- Visiting Malaysian Foreign Minister
Syed Hamid Albar said today that his China tour has been highly
successful and has yielded positive results.
</P>
<P>
Albar made the comment during a press conference following the
conclusion of the Joint Statement on Framework for Future
Bilateral Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said the framework agreement geared to the 21st century
covers the political, economic and defense arenas and will guide
the development of long-term, healthy and stable Sino-Malaysian
relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this year marks the 25th anniversary of the
establishment of diplomatic ties between the two countries. China
and Malaysia are important countries in Asia and China has played
an important role in the regional and international arenas,
according to Albar.
</P>
<P>
He said that Malaysia places high value on good relations with
China and will continue to enhance and promote both bilateral and
multilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Albar also pointed to the rapid development of trade relations
between Malaysia and China.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian businessmen have exhibited great interest in the
Chinese market, said Albar, adding that Chinese companies have
invested in many projects in his country. He said that high-
ranking Malaysian economic and trade officials will visit China
later this year to consult with Chinese counterparts on approaches
for further developing bilateral trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Albar said that Malaysia and China are good neighbors, and said
differences between the two should be properly settled through
consultations. He also said that disputes between countries in the
region should be resolved through peaceful negotiations. External
interference should not be allowed to internationalize disputes,
said Albar.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Kosovo issue can only be resolved by political
means and through negotiations and consultations with the
involvement of the U.N. Security council.
</P>
<P>
Albar also answered questions concerning regional and
international issues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
