<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Approves 10-Year Mass Communication Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has approved a
draft mass communication master plan for the next 10 years
designed to improve the media infrastructure and open the sector
to competition, said a Government House press release.
</P>
<P>
The draft, proposed by Thailand's National Economic and Social
Development Board, focuses on a broad range of issues concerning
the improvement and the distribution of mass communication,
information technology and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft, basic media infrastructure available to the
government, private, non-governmental and community sectors will
be developed to narrow discrepancies in quality.
</P>
<P>
Also to be ensured is the equal distribution of infrastructure
between urban and rural areas and enhanced ethics among media
producers.
</P>
<P>
Mass communication, information technology and
telecommunications operations would benefit from greater
managerial participation by local organizations and relevant
sectors, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The plan targets radio and television broadcasting, computer
networks and media consumers, as well as the process to monitor
them.
</P>
<P>
At least 50 percent of radio and television programs are to be
reserved for education, culture, national security and the public
interest.
</P>
<P>
Licensed operators of radio frequencies and television
broadcasts are 40 percent government agencies, 20 percent NGOs,
and 40 percent private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
