<HEADLINE> China Sells Surplus Imported Wheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zhengzhou Grain Wholesale
Market in central China's Henan Province auctioned 190,000 tons of
surplus imported wheat between May 26-28 at a price of 367.2
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Grain Reserve Administration said
the auction was held to reduce the stockpile of grain surplus in
order to make room for new grain and reduce maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
The official said the wheat, which was part of 600,000 tons of
wheat imported from Canada, the United States and Australia in
1996, was stored in 190 State reserve grain depots.
</P>
<P>
The central government previously allocated surplus grain to
lower administrative levels.
</P>
<P>
Analysts note that the new method shows the government's
increased awareness of the advantages of the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
The Zhengzhou market's annual grain trade volume ranges between
2.5 million to three million tons, or 10 percent of the country's
total volume of grain in circulation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
