<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Host Seventh International Fatigue Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 400 scientists from 36
countries and regions are expected to attend the Seventh
International Fatigue Congress scheduled for June 8-12 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The first-ever congress of its kind held in China will focus on
the latest developments in fatigue research and will offer an
opportunity for Chinese and foreign scientists in the field to
engage in academic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Fatigue science, which integrates research on materials,
mechanics and mechanisms, has a history of more than 160 years.
Experts note that related research is vitally important for ensure
the safety of aviation, energy, transportation and communications.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide statistics indicate that 80 percent of the fatal
accidents involving machinery are the result of fatigue, aging and
cracking of mechanical materials and structures.
</P>
<P>
The International Fatigue Congress has been held in Sweden,
Britain, the United States, Japan, Canada and Germany since 1981.
This year's congress will be jointly organized by the Beijing
Institute of Aeronautical Materials, the Shenyang Institute of
Metal Research under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and the
China Materials Research Society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
