<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Go to Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The second democratic general
election began in South Africa, with polling stations open early
in the morning, and in some places, voters queue up to make their
mark.
</P>
<P>
Voters in Umtata, Eastern Cape, began lining up at polling
stations well before they opened at 7 a.m. (0500 GMT), South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred people waited patiently in the dark outside
Umtata's city hall, which serves as the polling station.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 people were standing in line at the President
Hoerskool polling station at Ridgeway in the south of
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The polling station opened at exactly 7:00 a.m. and the voting
process appeared to be proceeding smoothly.  Voting kicked off to
a brisk start in Cape Town's southern suburbs, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
A snap survey of polling stations in the Wynberg, Plumstead and
 Constantia areas at 6.30 a.m. (0430 GMT) revealed fast-growing
queues of people braving the winter cold to cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
When the doors opened at the Alphen center polling station at 7
a.m., more than 100 people were patiently waiting in line outside
with more streaming in by the minute.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the door scanned voters' ID books before allowing
them to enter the building to cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
Polling stations will be closed at 9:00 p.m. (1900 GMT)
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
