<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Sea Fishing Ban Proceeds Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The first fishing ban in South
China Sea commenced on Tuesday and is proceeding smoothly,
according to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's fisheries department reports that a joint check
found only one boat illegally operating in the banned area.
</P>
<P>
The use of trawl nets is banned in an area north of 12 degrees
latitude, including the Beibu Gulf, between June 1 to July 31.
</P>
<P>
Yang Jian, director of the fisheries department, said the
purpose of the ban is to reduce excessive fishing and protect
marine resources. He noted that excessive fishing in recent years
has significantly depleted marine resources and caused a decline
in the output of aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
This year's moratorium idles 15,216 fishing vessels from
Guangdong and Hainan provinces, and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region. Some 15,202 vessels have been berthed and the fisheries
management departments is investigating to determine if the
remaining 14 vessels are berthed in other provinces.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some 1,879 vessels from Hong Kong and Macao have
also been berthed.
</P>
<P>
China's fishing ban in the East and Yellow seas since 1995 has
helped increase the annual output of aquatic products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
