<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Launches Internet Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the largest U.
S. stock brokerage, announced here Tuesday that it will allow
customers to trade stocks over the Internet for 29.95 U.S. dollars
per transaction.
</P>
<P>
"Whether clients want advice and guidance from a skilled
financial consultant, convenient, self-directed Internet investing,
or some combination, they'll get it at Merrill Lynch," David
Komansky, chairman and chief executive officer of the company,
said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The company made the decision in face of challenge for its
business from on-line traders such as Charles Schwab Corp. The
Internet now accounts for 30 percent to 35 percent of all stock
trades by individuals.
</P>
<P>
The company will also permit investors to do unlimited free
trading in return for an annual account fee equaling about 0.2
percent of the account's asset. Its minimum fee will be 1,500
dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The decision marks a dramatic change for Merrill Lynch after
spending decades to forge a nationwide network of 14,800 brokers,
who provide customers with investment advices and earn commissions
for placing stock trades. Analysts estimate that about two billion
dollars of Merrill's 1998 revenue of 17.5 billion dollars came
from commissions paid by individual investors for stock and bond
trades.
</P>
<P>
The Merrill's Internet service will be available starting
December this year. Clients who want to continue to deal with
Merrill as before -- advised by a broker and paying full
commissions, will still be able to do so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
