<HEADLINE> Buying Power of Vietnam's Rural Residents Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The buying power of Vietnam's rural
residents is continuing to decline, Vietnam's English daily
Vietnam News reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the Ministry of Planning and Investment
(MPI) showed that Vietnam's rural residents now buy only 29
percent of consumer goods in the country annually, despite
accounting for about 80 percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
The consumption ratio of rural residents has fallen
year-by-year, from 37.7 percent in 1996 to 30.66 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The MPI attributed the main reason for the decline to the low
average income of rural residents, which is 2 million Vietnamese
dong (VND) (145 U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
The figure falls further to below 1 million VND (72 U.S.
dollars) for residents in Vietnam's remote, mountainous and
natural calamity-prone areas.
</P>
<P>
Currently about 14 million people are classified as poor
throughout Vietnam and 90 percent of them are rural residents.
</P>
<P>
According to the standard set by Vietnam's Ministry of Labor,
War Invalids and Social Affairs, families which earn less than per
capita monthly income of 25 kilograms of rice or 90,000 VND (6.47
U.S. dollars) in urban areas, 20 kg of rice or 70,000 VND (5.03
U.S. dollars) in lowland rural areas, and 15 kg of rice equal to
55,000 VND (3.95 U.S. dollars) in the mountainous rural areas are
defined as poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
