<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Bonds Warmly Received In First Issue Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Thai investors Tuesday
flooded the Bank of Thailand's headquarters, its nationwide
offices and other agents, taking up to seven billion baht (191.8
million U.S. dollars) of the government bonds on the first
marketing day, The Nation reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank and its branches sold 1.03 billion baht (28.2
million dollars) of the 25 billion baht (684.9 million dollar)
bonds.
</P>
<P>
Most buyers were civil servants and retired officials who were
attracted by the after-tax return of 5.7375 percent of the
government bonds which are much higher than the deposit rates at
commercial banks which are between 4.0-4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Many of the investors said they wanted to spend part of their
entire savings on these bonds for the return, which is payable
semi-annually.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the central bank, other selling agents of the bonds
include the Government Savings Bank which successfully sold 2.06
billion baht (56.4 million dollar) bonds in the first day.
</P>
<P>
The overwhelming response from the public was beyond the
central banks' expectation.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand has been convinced that the
25-billion-baht bonds would be sold out before September, the end
of the 1998-99 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
