<HEADLINE> Good Harvest of Vietnam's Winter-Spring Crop in Sight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's winter-spring rice crop of
this year is expected to reach a record 13.9 million tons, 300,000
tons more than the previous one, Vietnam News said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the anticipated high output is that rice
fields have been expanded by 2,886 hectares, a 3.7 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
The provinces in Cuu Long (Mekong) Delta, Vietnam's biggest
granary, have already reaped their harvests, with an average
output of five tons per hectare, a slight drop of about 0.3 tons.
However, the total rice output in the southern delta is estimated
at 7.3 million tons, an increase of 123,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Song Hong (Red River) Delta provinces look set to produce more
rice than the previous crop as the area has a good irrigation
system. It is estimated that the northern delta will register a
per-hectare increase of 0.09 tons against the previous crop, with
a total output of 2.9 million tons, an increase of 43,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
However, provinces in the mid-land and mountainous areas of the
north of Vietnam have faced a prolonged drought, forcing the
conversion of 23,000 hectares to alternative crops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
