<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Belgian Ministers Resign Over Chicken Contamination Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Health Minister Marcel
Colla and Farm Minister Karel Pinxten resigned Tuesday amid a
scandal over contaminated chicken meat and eggs in the country as
the government announced a national ban on selling poultry
products.
</P>
<P>
The ministers handed in their resignations to King Albert II
after long discussions with Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Health Ministry ordered wholesalers to stop
selling chicken meat and eggs until they were proved free from the
cancer-causing chemical dioxin found in some chicken feed in
several farms.
</P>
<P>
High levels of the carcinogen was detected in late April in
chicken feed produced by nine Belgian companies, which were found
to have fortified the feed with banned animal fat.
</P>
<P>
The Farm Ministry launched a supervision over 350 chicken farms
that may have used the contaminated feed and in late May found
dioxin in chicken meat and eggs.
</P>
<P>
The contamination scandal has aroused strong reactions across
the European Union countries. France and Sweden have decided to
stop chicken imports from Belgium while Germany is considering
embargo against Belgian poultry.
</P>
<P>
The EU is also expected to announce the withdrawal from the 15
EU countries of the poultry products by 416 Belgian farms using
feed containing dioxin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
