<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation Declines by 0.28 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia registered a 0.28 percent
deflation or negative inflation in May, the country's third month
of deflation in a row, according to the Central Bureau of
Statistics (BPS).
</P>
<P>
"The negative monthly inflation rate was primarily caused by a
1.35 percent decline in the prices of basic food commodities,"
Chief of the BPS Sugito Suwito said.
</P>
<P>
He said a 0.15 percent decline in the prices of processed
foods, beverages, cigarettes and tobacco and a 1.03 percent drop
in the prices of clothing had contributed to the deflation.
</P>
<P>
"But the deflation rate is slowing particularly as prices of
other commodities, especially rice, have started to increase,"
Sugito was quoted by The Jakarta Post Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that prices in the housing, health, education,
recreation, sports, and telecommunications and transportation
sectors inflated in May.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia posted a deflation rate of 0.18 percent in March, and
0.68 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Sugito said that the relatively peaceful campaigning by the 48
political parties ahead of the June 7 general election and the
undisturbed distribution sector had helped in preventing price
rises.
</P>
<P>
The relatively stable exchange rate of the rupiah against the
U.S. dollar also contributed to the monthly deflation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sugito, however, declined to confirm whether the government
inflation target of 10 percent by the end of the 1999/2000 fiscal
year ending March would be attainable.
</P>
<P>
"There's still uncertainty surrounding the country's political
condition over the next six months," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government had projected an inflation target of 17 percent
for the current fiscal year, but has recently revised it to 10
percent following positive developments in the country's
macroeconomic picture.
</P>
<P>
"Looking at the production side, things are much better than
last year, therefore if there are no disturbances in distribution,
I believe this year's inflation could fall to a single digit
figure," Sugito added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
