<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Mounts Campaign to Protect Buddhist Statues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China is mounting an extensive
campaign to reduce heavy pollution of more than 50,000 ancient
Buddhist statues in the Yungang Grottos in the northern Shanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
Local government sources cited the major threat as dust and
sulfur dioxide created by coal trucks streaming along an adjacent
highway. They noted that dust particles and emissions blacken and
seriously deteriorate the beautiful statues built in the 4th
century.
</P>
<P>
Every day, some 16,000 coal trucks travel the highway 300
meters from the grottos which are located in a major coal
production center.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO is currently considering a bid to include the Yungang
Grottos on its list of World Cultural Heritages.
</P>
<P>
The central government plans spend 200 million yuan (25 million
US dollars) to construct a bypass which will reroute coal trucks
some 10 kilometers from the grottos.
</P>
<P>
A tree-lined special tourist highway to the grottos is
currently under construction. Coal trucks will be prohibited from
using the new artery.
</P>
<P>
Some 10,000 artisans completed the Yungang Grottos over a 60
year period. Most of the statues are housed in caves dug in the
face of a cliff stretching one kilometer. The largest statue is 17
meters high and the smallest is only two centimeters.
</P>
<P>
The artistic and academic value of the relics equals similar
works at Dunhuang on the Silk Road and at Longmen in Luoyang, a
major ancient city in central China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
