<HEADLINE> Ku Klux Klan Infiltrates Australia: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The notorious white supremacist
group Ku Klux Klan (KKK) in the United States has set up branches
in three leading states in Australia, two major Australian
newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald and Melbourne-based daily newspaper
The Age, said that through Australian citizen Peter Coleman, the
KKK had set up branches in Australia's most populous states of New
South Wales, Victoria and Queensland, with a growing membership
base of about 70 members.
</P>
<P>
Coleman, formerly a member of the Australian Nationalist
Movement, a racist group, is now a member of the anti-Asian
immigrant One Nation Party.
</P>
<P>
But One Nation Party National Director David Ettridge, on
hearing of Coleman's Klan ties, told Melbourne-based radio 3AW
Wednesday that he had immediately expelled Coleman from the party.
</P>
<P>
Coleman told the newspapers that he was happy "to shout from
the rooftops" that he was head of the racist organization.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is for a white Australia, a fair Australia," he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers ran photographs of Klan members in full KKK
outfits in a Sydney meeting house.
</P>
<P>
Barry E Black, an "Imperial Wizard" of the KKK, told 3AW Radio
from the U.S. Wednesday that the KKK was setting up in Australia
because it wanted white Australians to be proud of their heritage
and "wake up."
</P>
<P>
He said he had been in touch with Coleman several times and was
planning to come to Australia sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, there have been a series of KKK-style
attacks on aborigines in Queensland, east Australia, but local
police have denied the existence a Klan presence.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300,000 black-skinned aborigines in Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
