<HEADLINE> Disaster Prevention Meeting Starts in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 500 government officials and
experts from 30 countries of the American continent opened a four-
day meeting here Tuesday on the International Decennium for the
Reduction of Natural Disasters.
</P>
<P>
The agenda includes the evaluation of risks, prevention
programs, exchange of information, and strengthening of health and
education institutions in the region.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Acting President Astrid Fishel said in his speech
that Latin America and the Caribbean are frequently hit by natural
catastrophes, with extensive direct and indirect damages.
</P>
<P>
During the last 27 years, natural disasters have caused an
average of more than 4,000 deaths every year on the American
continent, affecting half a million people and leading to damages
of two billion U.S. dollars on a yearly basis, according to
reports from the Economic Commission for Latin America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Central America is not a region of isolated countries, Fishel
noted, but a group of nations "united in the grief of the great
tragedy caused by hurricane Mitch." The hurricane ravaged the
region between last October and November, leaving some 10,000 dead,
hundreds of thousands of homeless, and incalculable other damages.
</P>
<P>
Central American authorities warned that the hurricane season
of this year, which started Tuesday, might be more intense and
dangerous than that of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
