<HEADLINE> Romania Not to Join NATO's Ground Forces in Kosovo: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Foreign Minister Andrei
Plesu stressed here Tuesday that Romania would by no means
participate in NATO's ground military operation in Kosovo,
Yugoslavia, but would be willing to send peacekeeping troops after
the war.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Mediafax, Plesu said that his country was
deeply concerned that NATO was likely to send in combatant ground
forces to Kosovo, a southern Serbian province mostly inhabited by
independence-seeking ethnic Albanians, adding that ground
operation would cause heavy casualties.
</P>
<P>
The minister emphasized that even if NATO, which has conducted
air strikes against Yugoslavia for more than 60 days, requests
Romania to join in ground military actions in its neighbor, it
would on no account do it.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Romania would give a positive reply if the
military alliance asked it to dispatch a noncombatant force into
the troubled Serbian province to help peacekeeping after the end
of the war, but the Romanian team would not exceed 250 soldiers
under a parliamentary resolution passed last October.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian minister complained that NATO's continuous bombing
of Yugoslavia inflicted severe economic loss upon his country,
with foreign trade and tourism bearing the brunt.
</P>
<P>
Plesu cited the latest figures estimated by various departments
as showing Romania has suffered a total of 850 million U.S.
dollars in economic loss this year caused by the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
He urged the international community to find out an effective
way to compensate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
