<HEADLINE> Moldova, Ukraine Agree on Boundary Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Moldova and Ukraine reached a
final agreement on their controversial boundary demarcation
Tuesday in the Moldovan capital of Chisinau, the Moldovan News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached by an inter-governmental mixed committee
between the two countries, settled their seven-year-old land
disputes and paved the way for the signing of a final boundary
pact by their presidents next month, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Moldova will receive a piece of land 100
meter wide on its south, which extended the length of the Danube
River flowing through Moldovan territory to 800 meters from 700
meters.
</P>
<P>
In return, Moldova agreed to cede to Ukraine a seven-kilometer
railway section near the village of Palanca, which was built by
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to swap two pieces of land of the same
size near the city of Basarabeasca, to ensure the normal run of
their railways in that area.
</P>
<P>
Moldova and Ukraine delimited their boundaries temporarily in
early 1990s when they won independence from the former Soviet
Union. Since then, negotiations on boundary demarcation had made
little progress.
</P>
<P>
They are scheduled to officially sign a boundary pact during
Moldovan President Kirillovich Luchinsky's visit to Ukraine in
July, announced Moldovan Deputy Prime Minister Nicolae Andronic
and Ukrainian Prime Minister Sergei Tigipko Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
