<HEADLINE> FBI Hunts Hackers Who Attack Government Web Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) is hunting the computer hackers who attacked
five government Web sites recently, FBI and Justice Department
officials announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It's time-consuming and takes a lot of spade work, but we can
track down many of these hackers, and that's going on now," FBI
spokesman Frank Scafidi said.
</P>
<P>
"We'll catch a few, no matter how deep they hide in their
basements. Someone will go to jail for some real time. That will
have impact," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hackers who cause 5,000 dollars damage in one year can be
charged and sentenced to five years in prison, said Scott Charney,
head of the Justice Department's computer crime section.
</P>
<P>
Merely trespassing on a government computer, without
authorization and without causing a loss, can also bring up to one
year in jail.
</P>
<P>
Annoyed by the recent wave of attacks, White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart warned Tuesday that hackers who targeted federal
Internet sites would be caught and punished.
</P>
<P>
"For those who think that this is some sort of sport, I think (
it will be) less fun when the authorities do catch up with them...
and these people are prosecuted," he said.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, hackers attacked Web sites of the Department
of Energy, the FBI, the Senate, the Interior Department and the
White House.
</P>
<P>
The Web sites of the Interior Ministry and a federal super-
computer laboratory in Idaho were vandalized by hackers Monday
because of a related investigation of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
Computer crimes are increasing in recent years in the United
States as computer literacy grows.
</P>
<P>
A 1999 computer crime survey made by the Computer Security
Institute and the FBI's San Francisco office found that system
penetration by outsiders increased for the third year. Such
intrusions were reported by 30 percent of the 521 computer
security professionals surveyed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
