<HEADLINE> Indonesia Registers Trade Surplus in January-April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia registered an overall
trade surplus of 6,593.4 million U.S. dollars in January-April
1999, according to The Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS).
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's exports in the period totaled 13,912.3 million U.S.
dollars while its imports were recorded at 7,318.9 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The export figure, however, was lower by 13.95 percent than
that recorded for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first four months of this year, the country's
non-oil exports dropped by 14.79 percent from 13,380.2 million
U.S. dollars to 11,401.4 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country's oil exports were also down by 27.45 percent to
204.7 million U.S. dollars while gas exports were down by 21.41
percent to 1,113 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports during January-April amounted to 7,318.9 million U.S.
dollars, a drop of 19.82 percent compared with the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the BPS Sugito Suwito said the decline in the
country's imports was due to a drop in the value of
non-oil/non-gas imports.
</P>
<P>
Imports of commodities were down by 9.07 percent from 1,765.3
million U.S. dollars to 1,605.2 million U.S. dollars. Imports of
raw materials and capital goods also declined.
</P>
<P>
However, oil and gas imports rose by 9.28 percent from 175.6
million U.S. dollars to 191.9 million U.S. dollars, he was quoted
by national newspapers Wednesday as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
