<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Hold Mid-Year Gems Emporium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The state-run Myanmar Gems
Enterprise (MGE) will hold a mid-year gems emporium here in
October to put on sale the country's locally produced gems, jade,
pearl and jewelry through the tender system or competitive
bidding, the New Light of Myanmar said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local private entrepreneurs may also sell their gemstones and
jewelry at the state-sponsored emporium, the MGE was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to promote gems sales, Myanmar has held gems
emporiums in the capital annually since 1964 with additional
mid-year ones introduced since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The annual gems emporium in March this year fetched 6.3 million
U.S. dollars, while the last mid-year one held last October gained
4.29 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country earned a total of 271.3 million dollars from the
past 36 annual and seven mid-year gems emporiums.
</P>
<P>
The emporiums have attracted hundreds of gems merchants from
over a dozen countries and regions, mostly from China's Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region, Thailand, Japan and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The emporiums also draw gems traders from a number of local
private companies.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, a well-known producer of jade, ruby and sapphire in
the world, is striving to create a systematic gem market in line
with its market-oriented economic system introduced in late 1988.
</P>
<P>
In addition to permitting the local private sector to mine and
process gems in the country, the government has also set up joint
ventures with companies from Thailand, Malaysia and Israel to
carry out gems extraction and processing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
