<HEADLINE> Thailand to send 300 workers to Libya This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will send 300 workers to
Libya this year to boost labor cooperation between the two
countries, according to the Thai Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The plan was part of the outcome from last week's visit by
Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan to Libya.
</P>
<P>
An official at the Thai Foreign Ministry was quoted Wednesday
by the Bangkok Post as saying that Thai workers will be employed
in an ambitious man-made river construction project operated by a
South Korean company which could take 10 years to complete.
</P>
<P>
The new labor quota will add to some 6,500 Thai laborers
currently working in Libya as truck drivers, mechanics and
construction workers.
</P>
<P>
Surin was the first high-ranking representative from Asia to
visit Libya after the United Nations Security Council temporarily
lifted the 1992 sanctions against Libya on April 5, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution followed Tripoli's move in the same month
to hand over to an international tribunal two Libyan suspects in
the 1988 terrorist bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie,
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
In the area of economic cooperation, Surin asked Libya to buy
more Thai goods to correct a trade deficit with Bangkok. 
</P>
