<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jakarta Stock Exchange Ready For Millennium Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The president of the Jakarta Stock
Exchange (JSX), Mas Achmad Daniri, said the exchange was nearly
year 2000 compliant, the Jakarta Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Almost 100 percent of the hardware in the exchange's
infrastructure is Y2K compliant," Daniri was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, he said some minor problems in a few areas still
required further attention.
</P>
<P>
"Only some minor areas need fine-tuning," he said, adding that
the exchange was working with an Australian Y2K auditor firm.
</P>
<P>
The exchange's management has now turned its attention to
helping exchange members and listed companies reach Y2K
compliance.
</P>
<P>
According to the exchange's latest bulletin, of 46 exchange
members, only 20 were 100 percent Y2K compliant, and others were
between 75 percent to 25 percent compliant.
</P>
<P>
But the bulletin said most of the companies listed on the JSX
were nearly Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
As the next millennium approaches and with the press
progressively reporting the threats behind the millennium bug,
many local companies have become increasingly anxious about the
future of their computerized operations.
</P>
<P>
Y2K will become a problem on January 1, 2000, during which many
software in the world could be confusing and malfunctioning
because the software had not been set for programs after December
31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Many computer application programs have set two-digit dates
such as "00" to "99" of 1900 to 1999, so that in 2000 the
computers will read "00", and this will cause global confusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Tourist Arrivals in Indonesia Up This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- About 1.25 million foreign tourists
visited Indonesia in the first four months of this year, up by
5.22 percent from the corresponding period last year, according to
the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS).
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists entered Indonesian territory through 13
gateways. Among the gateways, Mataram, capital of West Nusa
Tenggara province, saw the highest increase in the number of
foreign tourist arrivals with 53.36 percent, followed by Ngurah
Rai (Bali) with 19.97 percent and Batam (Riau) with 19.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Most of the gateways registered an increase in the number of
tourist arrivals. But Adi Sumarmo gateway in Solo, Central Java,
Hasanudin gateway in Ujungpandang, South Sulawesi and Entikong
gateway in Pontianak, West Kalimantan, all suffered a nearly 60
percent drop.
</P>
<P>
Fluctuations in the number of tourist arrivals were closely
related to social, political and security developments at home,
Chief of the BPS Sugito Suwito said.
</P>
<P>
Citing an example, he said, the number of tourist arrivals in
April 1999 dropped 10.24 percent to 305,814 compared with the
previous month following rumors that political tensions in the
country would heighten prior to the June 7 polls.
</P>
<P>
Sugito also said the room occupancy rate at starrated hotels in
10 tourist destinations in April was 40.86 percent, up by 2.22
percent from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign tourists visiting Indonesia last year was
3.51 million, down by 16.97 percent from the previous year, Sugito
was quoted by Antara News Agency Wednesday as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
