<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Consumes More Gold in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China's gold consumption increased
in the first quarter this year compared with the same period last
year, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Gold demand on the mainland was 55 tons in the first three
months, up five percent on an annual basis, according to the World
Gold Council, an international organization established and funded
by leading gold mining companies around the world.
</P>
<P>
The latest report from the council indicates that the increased
sales of gold in China came from the jewelry sector.
</P>
<P>
The year 1999 symbolizes eternity, encouraging weddings during
the Chinese Lunar New Year, which fueled the consumption of gold
jewelry, the report said. Sales were also boosted during the time
as the Year of Rabbit makes gold gift more auspicious and promotes
rabbit motif collections as well as jewelry designs.
</P>
<P>
"It showed an upward trend in gold consumption because of the
availability of fashionable gold jewelry," Liu Shan'en, deputy
director of the Gold Economic Development Research Center was
quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"People can afford a well-designed quality ring with a price of
several hundred yuan (8.28 yuan is equal to one dollar)," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that sales of gold jewelry were strong
in most Chinese cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
