<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Continues Bombing on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 1 (Xinhua) -- NATO continued heavy bombing on much
of Yugoslavia overnight Monday and Tuesday, cutting off
electricity and water supplies in the capital city of Belgrade,
said media reports here.
</P>
<P>
The reports said 10 people were killed and 25 injured when NATO
warplanes struck a radio station in the southwestern town of Novi
Pazar mid-afternoon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
NATO missiles completely destroyed two major electricity
transformers in Belgrade, paralyzing the entire power and water
supplies in the capital city, including those in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
NATO warplanes increased their raids on a series of strategic
targets across Serbia in the past 24 hours, including electric
grids in Belgrade and Nis, the shelter of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and numerous military and civilian facilities.
</P>
<P>
They also bombed rail roads, arms depots, bunkers, warehouses,
radio and television transmitters in the past day. In Kosovo, the
southern province at the heart of NATO's war with Yugoslavia, some
50 missiles were fired on targets within hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
