<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakia Reinstates Import Customs Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Slovak government decided on
Tuesday to reinstate a 7 percent customs tariff on all imported
commodities so as to improve the country's current poor economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the restoration was merely a temporary measure, the
government announced at the same time that the tariff is expected
to be reduced to 5 percent on January 1, 2000 and further down to
3 percent on July 1, 2000. And in early 2001, it would be
completely abolished.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia adopted the zero customs tariff policy on October 1,
1998. However the country's economic growth slowed down in the
following seven months. Financial deficits were reported and
foreign trade deficit remained high. The rate of exchange between
koruna and major western currencies countries sank to a record low.
</P>
<P>
Facing the severe situation, the government had to adopt a
series of austerity measures including the restoration of import
customs tariff, through which, the government is expected to
increase its revenue by 10.1 billion more korun (224.4 million U.S.
dollars) this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
