<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates of U.S. Treasury Bills Rise in Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Interest rates on short-term U.S.
Treasury securities rose in Tuesday's auction to the highest level
in nearly nine months.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury Department sold 7.5 billion dollars in three-month
bills at a discount rate of 4.620 percent, up from 4.495 percent
last week. Another 7.5 billion dollars in six-month bills were
sold at a rate of 4.750 percent, up from 4.570 percent.
</P>
<P>
Both rates of the three-month and the six-month bills were the
highest since September 1998.
</P>
<P>
The new discount rates understate the actual return to
investors -- 4.753 percent for three-month bills, with a 10,000
dollar bill selling for 9,883.20 dollars, and 4.947 percent for a
six-month bill selling for 9,759.90 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the U.S. Federal Reserve reported Tuesday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, jumped to 4.93
percent last week from 4.89 percent in the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
