<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Volleyball Federation Lifts Ban on Bulgarian Clubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Volleyball
Federation (FIVB) officially recognized the newly-elected
leadership of the Bulgarian Volleyball Federation (BVF) and lifted
the ban on Bulgarian volleyball clubs from taking part in
international events, the FIVB press office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Ralph Andressen, Vice-President of the FIVB, attended the
BVF general meeting, held May 30 in Sofia, which elected a new
management. He confirmed that the meeting followed the FIVB
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The BVF general meeting elected Agriculture Minister Ventsislav
Vurbanov as BVF president and the newly-elected governing council
elected Tsvetan Pavlov as BVF secretary general.
</P>
<P>
The ban stemmed from quarrels that started in December 1998. On
December 23, 1998, Dimiter Zlatanov was elected BVF president, but
FIVB did not recognize the new leadership and twice confirmed that
Vladimir Zayakov was the only BVF chairman which it recognized.
</P>
<P>
As the representatives of the two federations did not reach an
agreement, on March 24 FIVB imposed a one-month ban on all
Bulgarian clubs from participation in international volleyball
events, which it later extended till May 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
