<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders Intensified Drive Against Youth Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
concerned over youth violence in the country, ordered a government
investigation Tuesday into the link of entertainment with youth
violence.
</P>
<P>
"Our children are being fed a dependable daily dose of violence
" that amounts to the typical child witnessing 40,000 play murders
and 200,000 dramatized acts of violence by his 18th birthday,
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Such a barrage blurs the line between "fantasy and reality
violence" for too many young people, Clinton said when announcing
the order at a White House event as the latest initiative to fight
against youth violence after the campus shooting incident in
Colorado in April.
</P>
<P>
"I know this stuff sells, but that does not make it right," he
said. "The time has come to show some restraint."
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department and the Federal Trade Commission will
spend one million dollars and take 18 months to carry out the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the federal investigators will "study the extent
to which the video game, music and movie makers do actually market
violence to children" and whether those industries only laxly
restrict sales to minors.
</P>
<P>
Also White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the study could
provide a basis for new laws or regulations, and left open the
possibility of using subpoenas to make companies reveal
information about their advertising.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's announcement came three weeks after he convened a
summit meeting of the industries of movies, video games, Internet
and guns to combat youth violence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990602.0306 </DOCNO>
