<HEADLINE> New Salvadoran President Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Economist Francisco Flores, a
member of the ruling Republican Nationalist Alliance (Arena), was
sworn in on Tuesday as the 34th President of El Salvador for the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
The new President said in his inaugural address that he would
encourage the business circle to create jobs, the only choice
against poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
Flores, 39, who won in March the presidential elections against
other six candidates, succeeds his party comrade Armando Calderon
Sol.
</P>
<P>
El Salvador registered a 7.5 percent unemployment rate last
year, while poverty affects more than half of its 5.6 million
population.
</P>
<P>
A long civil war between guerrillas and a succession of
military and U.S. supported rightist governments plunged the
country into poverty and claimed lives of more than 75,000 people
from 1979 to 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
