<HEADLINE> Colombian President to Secure Release of Abducted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Andres Pastrana is returning home Tuesday from abroad earlier than
scheduled to seek the release of 60 people held by rebels.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said the president cut short his visit "for the
security of the country."
</P>
<P>
Pastrana will go to Cali, southwest of Colombia to attend a
security meeting in order to achieve the release of the people.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana had been in Canada since Sunday, when guerrillas from
Colombia's second-largest rebel group, the National Liberation
Army (ELN), seized 144 worshippers from a church in the western
city of Cali and trucked them into the nearby mountains.
</P>
<P>
ELN abandoned 84 of its captives hours later to pursuing troops.
</P>
<P>
It had not publicly taken responsibility for the abduction,
which shocked even the Colombians accustomed to frequent guerrilla
kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
Observers here called the abduction a "desperate call for
attention" by the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said ELN appeared attempting to persuade
President Pastrana to take it more seriously in talks to end the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana has started peace talks with the largest rebel group --
15,000-member Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, but attempts
to talk with ELN have failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
