<HEADLINE> Philippines Expects 3.7 Pct GNP Growth This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The gross national product (GNP) of
the Philippines is expected to surge to 3.7 percent this year from
only 0.1 percent in 1998, the Journal newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The uptick would exceed the 3.5 percent growth targeted under
the country's program with the International Monetary Fund, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu was quoted as saying that
the gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to hit three percent
as projected by government planners earlier.
</P>
<P>
He said the forecast was based on actual growth performance in
the first quarter this year which "surprised" the government when
GNP grew by two percent and GDP grew by 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu vowed that the pump-priming activities of the
government, which commits public spending in so-called
growth-sensitive areas of agriculture, infrastructure, low-cost
housing, education and health, would not be stopped.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue with pump-priming until the private sector
has responded in a positive way," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
