<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auto Sector Goes into E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An e-commerce network for the
automobile sector was inaugurated Tuesday amid high expectations
of driving China's auto industry to roll faster and move closer to
international standards.
</P>
<P>
The China Automotive Rainbow Net (CARN) is designed to enable
companies in the sector, including manufacturers, auto parts
supplies and dealers, to conduct bidding, auctions and business
negotiations through the net, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
It will also provide an electronic data interchange service so
that manufacturers can purchase parts and materials, establish a
sales management system and supervise branches nationwide.
</P>
<P>
China's major auto producers, such as First Automobile Works,
Dongfeng Motor Group and Shanghai Automotive (Group) Corp. have
expressed an interest to use e-commerce to reduce costs for
purchases, optimize the structure of inventories, slash marketing
costs and improve service efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The system is also linked to e-commerce networks in the United
States, Japan and Europe, with China Construction Bank and China
Merchants Bank acting as the clearing banks for business conducted
through the net.
</P>
<P>
The address of the website is www.cn-rainbow.com.  
</P>
</TEXT>
