<HEADLINE> Pacers Seek to Draw Even with Knicks in Eastern Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- After losing at home in the
playoffs for the first time in the Larry Bird era, the Indiana
Pacers seek to draw even with the New York Knicks tonight in the
Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
New York, the first eighth-seeded team to reach the conference
finals, snapped Indiana's 12-game postseason home winning streak
with a 93-90 victory in the series opener.
</P>
<P>
Indiana became the first team since the 1993 Chicago Bulls to
sweep the first two rounds of the playoffs, but squandered a five-
point lead in the final 2:20 on Sunday. Patrick Ewing scored six
of his 16 points down the stretch to lead the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
But the loss apparently has not shaken Indiana's confidence.
</P>
<P>
"The bottom line is a team to beat us four times," said Pacers
point guard Mark Jackson. "When we play our type of basketball,
we're not going to be beat."
</P>
<P>
The Knicks have won six straight playoff games, including four
in a row on the road. New York is 5-1 away from home in the
palyoffs after going just 8-17 during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
After tonight's game, the teams will enjoy a three-day break
before the series shifts to New York on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Portland Trail Blazers have three days to regroup after
dropping the first two games of the Western Conference finals in
San Antonio. 
</P>
