<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cavaliers Fire Coach Mike Fratello </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- After missing the playoffs for
only the third time this decade, the Cleveland Cavaliers today
fired coach Mike Fratello.
</P>
<P>
The shakeup in the Cavaliers' organization continued when
longtime general manager Wayne Embry stepped down and was replaced
by Jim Paxson, the team's vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
There were rumors of friction between Fratello and Embry, but
the pair was able to work together for six seasons. The Cavaliers
made the postseason four times during the duo's tenure but never
advanced past the first round.
</P>
<P>
"Although Coach Fratello has at least one more year on his
contract, we feel it is best to move forward under a new floor
leader right now," said Cavaliers owner Gordon Gund. "Because of
that and also to enable Coach Fratello to move forward, we have
made this change at this time."
</P>
<P>
Cleveland won 47 games three times under Fratello, who had the
team play a slow-down style to overcome a lack of offensive talent.
The Cavaliers led the league in defense during the 1996-97 season
but failed to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
Fratello led Cleveland to a 248-212 record in six years at the
helm and owns a career coaching mark of 572-462. He coached
Atlanta for seven seasons from 1983-1990, leading the Hawks to
four straight 50-win seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
