<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, June 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said on
Tuesday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) will
not compromise on its demand that the alliance be "at the core" of
any security force that enters Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"By being at the core, that means there must be a command and
control structure that is NATO's in charge of any peacekeeping
operation," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after addressing a suburban Washington
high school, Cohen said that NATO is planning to put as many as 50,
000 armed troops in a peacekeeping force. (US-NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
Tuesday met Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini as part of a
series of meetings with allied leaders aimed at demonstrating
allied unity on NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
The allies differ on the ground troops deployment, a pause in
the bombing campaign against Yugoslavia and targeting of the
bombing. (US-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Yugoslavia Tuesday reported a "dramatic
increase in civilian casualties" in the Balkan country in the wake
of recent NATO raids.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the Yugoslav Mission to the U.N. said
that more than 50 persons have been killed and more than 100
others wounded in the last 48 hours all over the country as NATO
continued its indiscriminate pounding of Serbia, a Yugoslav
republic.
</P>
<P>
"In certain cities and towns, the clearing away of debris is
still under way, so that it is feared that the number of
casualties could increase," the press release said. (UN-
Yugoslavia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Substantial progress has been achieved in diplomatic
negotiations to settle the Kosovo crisis, German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a late evening joint press conference with three
Kosovo mediators after their meeting at the Petersberg guest house
near Bonn, Schroeder said he was pleased that their talks were "
positive".
</P>
<P>
The three mediators are European Union (EU) envoy, Finnish
President Martti Ahtisaari, Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, and
U.S. deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott. (Schroeder-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- NATO fighter jets Tuesday repeatedly dropped guided
bombs on the Albanian side of border near the Morina border
crossing.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian news agency ATA reported that NATO warplanes
first attacked the Morina village, about 500 meters from the
border crossing, when the day was about to break.
</P>
<P>
At least three government defensive bunkers, in which Albanian
borderguards sheltered against Serb shellings just a day ago, were
destroyed in the early-morning NATO attack. (Albania-NATO-Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- A British committee said on Tuesday that NATO had
changed its tactics on Yugoslavia and was violating Geneva
Conventions.
</P>
<P>
"NATO has changed tack in recent days. It has intensified its
bombing of civilian targets," Alice Mahon, Parliament Member (MP)
from the Labor Party who chairs the Committee for Peace in the
Balkans, said in a statement issued on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said NATO "is now violating the Geneva
Conventions on the protection of civilian life on a routine daily
basis". (UK-Committee-NATO) 
</P>
</TEXT>
