<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinnear to Leave Wimbledon Football Club </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Joe Kinnear is set to step aside as
Wimbledon manager and pave the way for the appointment of Egil
Olsen, Dons chairman Sam Hammam revealed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kinnear, who missed the last two months of the season after
suffering a heart attack in March, has revealed he wants to manage
a bigger club, Hammam told BBC Radio 5 Live.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations have begun with former Norway coach Egil Olsen,
who is now in charge of part-timers Valerenga, Hammam added.
</P>
<P>
A deal could be struck within the next 24 hours to bring Olsen
to Selhurst Park -- as long as Wimbledon can negotiate a
compensation deal with Valerenga.
</P>
<P>
Kinnear -- the second longest-serving Premiership manager after
Alex Ferguson -- has not secured a new job and Hammam said he
would be staying with the Dons until his future has been resolved.
</P>
<P>
"It isn't the usual way a manager leaves a club -- this is
Wimbledon and we are doing it together," Hammam said.
</P>
<P>
Kinnear will play a part in the selection of the new manager
and will then help him settle into the club.
</P>
<P>
"Joe will stay with the club for as long as it takes and until
he finds the job he aspires to," Hammam added.
</P>
<P>
"He is part and parcel of what we are doing now and in the
future -- until such time as he finds a new job.
</P>
<P>
"It's all being done in the most loving way possible."
</P>
<P>
Hammam dismissed reports that the decision to appoint a new
manager had anything to do with Kinnear's recent ill health.
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon failed to win a match following his heart attack and
they slumped to 16th place -- their lowest Premiership finish.
</P>
<P>
"Joe has made a 100% recovery," Hammam said. "In fact he is
much better than before (the heart attack).
</P>
<P>
"I was overjoyed when I heard that Joe had been given a clean
bill of health -- but I was heartbroken when he dropped the
bombshell that he wants to leave Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
"Joe is more than my manager, he is my greatest pal -- not just
in the game but in my whole life and I couldn't believe what he
was telling me.
</P>
<P>
"But I must stress that no other club is involved and if and
when it happens I will help Joe achieve his aspirations and will
personally drive Joe to his first day of training wherever it is.
That is how much I love the man."
</P>
<P>
Olsen's arrival at Wimbledon is likely to be secured within the
next day or so, according to Norwegian television station TV2.
</P>
<P>
"If the two clubs can agree on a compensation, and that could
happen this evening, Olsen could be on his way to London tomorrow,
" revealed Fin Gnatt, sports editor of TV2.
</P>
<P>
"He (Olsen) didn't mention Joe Kinnear at all. I don't know
what Kinnear's position would be -- but it is the full managerial
position we are talking about as far as Egil Olsen is concerned.
</P>
<P>
"He (Olsen) told us that there were two teams in the world that
he had always dreamed of managing -- one was the Brazilian
national team and the other was Wimbledon," Gnatt added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
