<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended mixed
Tuesday in a mixed bag of economic signals.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 36.52 at
10,596.26. The Dow fell as mush as 150 points earlier in the
trading.
</P>
<P>
But the Standard and Poor's 500 index was down 7.58 at
1,294.26 and the technology heavy Nasdaq index was down 58.94 at
2,412,03.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, a prominent research group, reported
that the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, a key gauge of
future U.S. economic activity, fell 0.1 percent to 107.1 in
April, suggesting some softening in the economy,
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department also reported that construction
spending fell by a sharp 2.4 percent in April, the biggest
monthly decline in more than five years. The results indicated
that the economy is not overheating.
</P>
<P>
But the National Association of Purchasing Management
reported strong prices rises in raw materials in May for the
first time in 16 months, renewing fears among investors about
higher interest rates. The Federal Reserve warned two weeks
ago that it would raise interest rates to cool off the economy
if inflation is building up.
</P>
<P>
The late afternoon rally around cyclical stocks pulled the
Dow index out the negative territory and moved it into positive
one. Among the leading Dow components were Aluminum company
Alcoa and international Paper.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The NYSE composite
index fell 0.98 at 621.28 and the American Stock Exchange
composite index fell 2.63 at 776.11. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 1.22 at 437.46.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,568 down, 1,422 up and
544 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 681.99 million shares from 648.93
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
