<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Jets Repeatedly Bomb North Albanian Border Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- NATO fighter jets Tuesday repeatedly
dropped guided bombs on the Albanian side of border near the
Morina border crossing.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian news agency ATA reported that NATO warplanes first
attacked the Morina village, about 500 meters from the border
crossing, when the day was about to break.
</P>
<P>
At least three government defensive bunkers, in which Albanian
borderguards sheltered against Serb shellings just a day ago, were
destroyed in the early-morning NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
Five 10-meter-deep huge craters created by the NATO bombs
dotted the hilly terrains bordering Kosovo, a southern Serbian
province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Telephone lines were damaged.
</P>
<P>
The ATA said that two Albanian soldiers suffered minor injuries
when one bomb landed near their position.
</P>
<P>
The English marking on a piece of bomb fragments --"For Use on
MK-82.Fin Guided Bomb" indicated that it was the work of NATO.
</P>
<P>
Before noon, NATO warplanes came back again, hit the same area
with at least seven guided bombs, and sent about 50 people,
including Albanian soldiers and some 20 journalists running for
shelter in panic.
</P>
<P>
The puzzled 1,500 villagers, and some Kosovo refugees who
stayed with them, started to evacuate from the Morina village this
morning.
</P>
<P>
They had managed to stay in the village despite Serb artillery
pounding but they were now under bombing of NATO, which they
believed was on their side.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been reportedly helping the Kosovo Liberation Army
(KLA) in the raging fierce fightings over the past week between
KLA and Serb troops the nearby hills on the Kosovo side of border.
</P>
<P>
KLA rebels, seen by Belgrade as terrorists, have been trying to
open a supply corridor running from the border area of Albania to
Prizren, a Kosovo city about 30 kilometers from the Morina border
crossing.
</P>
<P>
As each day passes, the situation on the northeast border of
Albania becomes increasingly tense and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
To review the worsening situation on the border, Albanian
President Rexhep Meidani called an emergency meeting on Monday
night. At the meeting, it was decided to intensify military
actions against what the Albanians say Serb provocations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
