<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More U.S. Households Expected to Be Banking Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, June 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 32 million households
in the United States are expected to be banking online by 2003,
according to a research released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Online banking is becoming fast a convenient functionality in
the country craved by the growing horde of Internet users. In
1998, there were already 6.6 million U.S. households banking
online, said the U.S. market research firm International Data
Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
Describing factors driving the explosive growth in online
banking, IDC said that there has been a proliferation of low-cost
PCs and other networking devices in the home market, which is
causing a surge in the number of Internet users. "Because many of
the security concerns have been alleviated," the research firm
said, "these Internet users are becoming comfortable using the
Internet as a transaction-based medium."
</P>
<P>
The increasing number of banks offering Web-based banking
services is also triggering the market's growth. IDC estimates the
number of banks in the United States offering online services will
increase from 1,150 in 1998 to more than 15,800 by 2003, primarily
via the Web. These numbers represent 6 percent and 86 percent
respectively of all U.S. commercial banks and credit unions.
</P>
<P>
A strong link exists between banking, bill payments and the
Internet, IDC said. "Although there is still uncertainty in the
bill presentment market," the research firm said, "banks must
seize this tremendous opportunity in front of them. Online banking
may be the critical service that enables banks to maintain their
role as the dominant provider of financial services." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
