<HEADLINE> Schroeder: Substantial Progress on Kosovo Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Substantial progress has been achieved
in diplomatic negotiations to settle the Kosovo crisis, German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a late evening joint press conference with three
Kosovo mediators after their meeting at the Petersberg guest house
near Bonn, Schroeder said he was pleased that their talks were
"positive".
</P>
<P>
The three mediators are European Union (EU) envoy, Finnish
President Martti Ahtisaari, Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, and
U.S. deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Ahtisaari, Chernomyrdin and Talbott had held
another meeting on solving the Kosovo crisis. And Chernomyrdin is
due to fly to Belgrade together with Ahtisaari on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he was hopeful that a joint statement with
Yugoslav leadership would be achieved in Chernomyrdin and
Ahtisaari's visit.
</P>
<P>
And again he underlined Russia's importance in seeking a
peaceful solution to Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
"A durable peace in Kosovo will never be possible without
Russian participation," said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said he was "fully confident" after the meeting
with his partners. He stressed Russia must take part in the
international presence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
What kind of achievement they will make in Belgrade during the
following days is now depending on the Yugoslav leadership, said
Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic negotiations must be based on current principles
raised by NATO and EU, he stressed, saying "I don't think we need
to bring anything new, and our negotiations are on the basis of
the principles that he has known."
</P>
<P>
More detailed mediating works are still needed to solve the
Kosovo crisis, but he and his partners have been fully prepared
for the exceedingly hard work, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing will prevent us from seeking a peaceful solution,"
said Ahtisaari.  
</P>
</TEXT>
