<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Positive Forces Omened to Drive Global Consulting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Consulting spending in the United
States is predicted to grow 14.8 percent to reach about 55 billion U.S.
dollars by 2003, a leading U.S. data provider said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Besides the strong U.S. market where the economy continues to
be robust, most global regions are expected to see the effects of
positive market drivers outweigh the negative ones, said the
Massachusetts-based International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
IDC termed the positive forces as those typically related to
mergers and acquisitions, deregulation and privatization,
technological advancement, restructuring, globalization and the
new digital economy.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing, government, communications and banking are the
biggest spenders on global consulting services, especially on
information technology(IT) consulting, said IDC in its latest
report on worldwide consulting Services 1996-2003.
</P>
<P>
Financial services, banking, retail and communications are seen
as some of the fastest-growing uses.
</P>
<P>
By type of consulting service, IT design and IT strategy
continue to represent the lion's share of the consulting market,
but services related to change management and business strategy
experience are growing the fastest.
</P>
<P>
These two consulting services are supported by a strong demand
for Internet services or E-commerce, customer relationship
management and supply chain management.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
